{{Elon Musk series}}

'''Tesla, Inc.''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|t|ɛ|s|l|ə}} {{respell|TESS|lə}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|t|ɛ|z|l|ə}} {{respell|TEZ|lə}}{{efn|According to company representatives, both pronunciations are correct,<ref>{{cite web|title=What's the correct way to pronounce 'Tesla'? We asked.|date=July 13, 2017 |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/whats-correct-way-pronounce-tesla-asked-181021888.html|access-date=October 6, 2021|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|language=en-US}}</ref> though [[Nikola Tesla]]'s surname is properly pronounced TESS-lə.}}) is an American multinational [[automotive]] and [[clean energy]] company headquartered in [[Austin, Texas]]<!-- Do not link Austin and Texas separately, search MOS:GEOLINK for further guidance. -->. Tesla designs and manufactures [[electric vehicle]]s ([[electric car]]s and [[electric truck|trucks]]), battery [[energy storage]] from home to [[Grid-scale storage|grid-scale]], [[solar panel]]s and [[Solar roof shingles|solar roof tiles]], and related products and services. Tesla is one of the [[list of public corporations by market capitalization|world's most valuable companies]] and, {{as of|2023|lc=y}}, is the world's most valuable automaker. In 2022, the company had the most worldwide sales of [[battery electric vehicle]]s, capturing 18% of the market. Through its subsidiary [[Tesla Energy]], the company develops and is a major installer of [[photovoltaic system]]s in the United States. Tesla Energy is also one of the largest global suppliers of battery energy storage systems, with 6.5{{nbsp}}[[gigawatt-hours]] (GWh) installed in 2022.

Tesla was incorporated in July 2003 by [[Martin Eberhard]] and [[Marc Tarpenning]] as Tesla Motors. The company's name is a tribute to inventor and electrical engineer [[Nikola Tesla]]. In February 2004, via a $6.5&nbsp;million investment, [[Elon Musk]] became the largest shareholder of the company. He has served as CEO since 2008. According to Musk, the purpose of Tesla is to help expedite the move to [[Sustainable energy economy|sustainable transport and energy]], obtained through electric vehicles and solar power. Tesla began production of its first car model, the [[Tesla Roadster (first generation)|Roadster]] sports car, in 2008. This was followed by the [[Tesla Model S|Model S]] sedan in 2012, the [[Tesla Model X|Model X]] SUV in 2015, the [[Tesla Model 3|Model 3]] sedan in 2017, the [[Tesla Model Y|Model Y]] crossover in 2020, and the [[Tesla Semi]] truck in 2022. The company plans to start production of the [[Cybertruck]] light-duty [[pickup truck]] in 2023.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crider |first1=Johnna |title=Tesla Cybertruck to enter limited production this Summer |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-limited-production-summer-2023/ |website=Teslarati |date=January 26, 2023 |publisher=Teslarati |access-date=30 January 2023}}</ref> The Model 3 is the all-time bestselling plug-in electric car worldwide, and in June 2021 became the first electric car to sell 1&nbsp;million units globally.<ref name=1miModel3 /> Tesla's 2022 full year deliveries were around 1.31&nbsp;million vehicles, a 40% increase over the previous year,<ref name = productiondeliveries/><ref name=Tesla4Q2021final /> and cumulative sales totaled 3&nbsp;million cars as of August 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Leswing |first=Kif |title=Elon Musk says Tesla has made over 3 million cars |date=August 14, 2022 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/08/14/elon-musk-says-tesla-has-made-over-3-million-cars.html |access-date=September 6, 2022 |publisher=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> In October 2021, Tesla's market capitalization reached $1&nbsp;trillion, the sixth company to do so in U.S. history.

Tesla has been the subject of several lawsuits, government scrutiny, journalistic [[Criticism of Tesla, Inc.|criticism]], and public controversies arising from statements and acts of CEO Elon Musk and from allegations of [[whistleblower]] retaliation, [[worker rights]] violations, and defects with their products.

{{TOC limit|3}}

== History ==
{{Main|History of Tesla, Inc.}}
[[File:Tesla Roadster Sport insignia (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Tesla Motors insignia as seen on a [[Tesla Roadster (first generation)|Tesla Roadster]], {{circa|2010}}]]

=== Founding (2003–2004) ===
The company was incorporated as Tesla Motors, Inc. on July 1, 2003, by [[Martin Eberhard]] and [[Marc Tarpenning]].{{sfn|Vance|2015|p=152}} Eberhard and Tarpenning served as CEO and CFO, respectively.<ref name=timelinefacts /> Eberhard said he wanted to build "a car manufacturer that is also a technology company", with its core technologies as "the battery, the computer software, and the proprietary motor".<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 30, 2007 |title=Tesla: A Carmaker With Silicon Valley Spark |language=en |work=Bloomberg.com |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2007-07-29/tesla-a-carmaker-with-silicon-valley-spark |access-date=August 31, 2020}}</ref>

Ian Wright was Tesla's third employee, joining a few months later.{{sfn|Vance|2015|p=152}} In February 2004, the company raised $7.5&nbsp;million in [[series A funding]], including $6.5&nbsp;million from Elon Musk, who had received $100&nbsp;million from the sale of his interest in [[PayPal]] two years earlier. Musk became the chairman of the board of directors and the largest shareholder of Tesla.{{sfn|Vance|2015|p=154}}<ref name="TC_history_2014">{{Cite news | last=Burns | first=Matt |date=October 8, 2014 | title=A Brief History of Tesla | url=https://techcrunch.com/gallery/a-brief-history-of-tesla/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717064829/https://techcrunch.com/gallery/a-brief-history-of-tesla/#/slide2 | archive-date=July 17, 2015 |access-date=June 11, 2015 |website=[[TechCrunch]] | quote="Tesla was founded not by Elon Musk, but rather by Martin Eberhard and Marc Tarpenning in July 2003. The two bootstrapped the fledgling auto company until [[Elon Musk]] led the company's US$7.5&nbsp;million Series A financing round in February 2004."}}</ref><ref name=timelinefacts>{{cite news |last1=Reed |first1=Eric |title=History of Tesla: Timeline and Facts |url=https://www.thestreet.com/technology/history-of-tesla-15088992 |work=[[TheStreet.com]] | date=February 4, 2020}}</ref> [[J. B. Straubel]] joined Tesla in May 2004 as [[chief technical officer]].{{sfn|Vance|2015|p=155}}

A lawsuit settlement agreed to by Eberhard and Tesla in September 2009 allows all five – Eberhard, Tarpenning, Wright, Musk, and Straubel – to call themselves co-founders.<ref>{{Cite news |last=LaMonica |first=Martin |title=Tesla Motors founders: Now there are five |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/tesla-motors-founders-now-there-are-five/ |publisher=[[CNET]] | date=September 21, 2009}}</ref>

=== Roadster (2005–2009) ===
{{Main|Tesla Roadster (first generation)}}

Elon Musk took an active role within the company and oversaw Roadster product design at a detailed level, but was not deeply involved in day-to-day business operations.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mitchell |first=Russ| title=Review: A deep new history of Tesla takes the shine off Elon Musk |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2021-07-30/power-play-tesla-book-review| date=July 30, 2021 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]]| url-access=limited}}</ref> The company's strategy was to start with a premium sports car aimed at early adopters and then move into more mainstream vehicles, including sedans and affordable compacts.<ref name="MasterPlan">{{cite web |last=Musk |first=Elon |title=The Secret Tesla Motors Master Plan (just between you and me) No. 124 |url=https://www.tesla.com/blog/secret-tesla-motors-master-plan-just-between-you-and-me |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802142703/http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/secret-tesla-motors-master-plan-just-between-you-and-me | archive-date=August 2, 2010 |date=August 2, 2006 |website=tesla.com |publisher=Tesla Motors}} {{Self-published source|inline|date=May 2015}}</ref>

In February 2006, Musk led Tesla's Series B [[venture capital funding]] round of $13&nbsp;million, which added Valor Equity Partners to the funding team.<ref>{{cite web |last=Weinstock |first=Suzanne |title=Venture-backed Tesla cuts costs |url=https://www.privateequityinternational.com/venture-backed-tesla-cuts-costs/ |website=Private Equity International| date=January 5, 2013}}</ref><ref name="TC_history_2014" /> Musk co-led the third, $40&nbsp;million round in May 2006 which saw investment from prominent entrepreneurs including Google co-founders [[Sergey Brin]] and [[Larry Page]], and former [[eBay]] President [[Jeff Skoll]].<ref name="GreenGiants">{{cite book |last1=Williams |first1=E. Freya |title=Green giants : how smart companies turn sustainability into billion-dollar businesses |date=2015 |location=New York |isbn=978-0-8144-3614-1 }}</ref> A fourth round worth $45&nbsp;million in May 2007 brought the total private financing investment to over $105&nbsp;million.<ref name="GreenGiants" />

Tesla's first car, the Roadster, was officially revealed to the public on July 19, 2006, in [[Santa Monica, California]], at a 350-person invitation-only event held in [[Barker Hangar]] at Santa Monica Airport.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://electrek.co/2016/07/19/tesla-roadster-debut-10-years-ago-gallery/ | title=Tesla launched the Roadster exactly 10 years ago and came out of stealth mode – Here's a trip down memory lane | first=Fred | last=Lambert | work=[[Electrek]] | date=July 19, 2016}}</ref>

In August 2007, Eberhard was asked by the board, led by Elon Musk, to step down as CEO.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/tesla-ceo-steps-down-as-possible-delays-loom/ | title=Tesla CEO steps down as possible delays loom | first=Michael | last=Kanellos | publisher=[[CNET]] | date=August 13, 2007}}</ref> Eberhard then took the title of "President of Technology" before ultimately leaving the company in January 2008. Co-founder Marc Tarpenning, who served as the Vice President of Electrical Engineering of the company, also left the company in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=Martin Eberhard and Marc Tarpenning {{!}} American entrepreneurs |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Martin-Eberhard-and-Marc-Tarpenning |website=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]}}</ref> In August 2007, Michael Marks was brought in as interim CEO, and in December 2007, [[Ze'ev Drori]] became CEO and President.<ref name="the-origin" /> Musk succeeded Drori as CEO in October 2008.<ref name="the-origin">{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-the-origin-story-2014-10 |title=The Making Of Tesla: Invention, Betrayal, And The Birth Of The Roadster|last=Baer|first=Drake | work=[[Business Insider]] |date=November 11, 2014}}</ref> In June 2009, Eberhard filed a lawsuit against Musk for allegedly forcing him out.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gigaom.com/2009/06/11/tesla-founder-eberhard-files-lawsuit-against-tesla-elon-musk/ |title=Tesla Founder Eberhard Files Lawsuit Against Tesla's Elon Musk |last=Fehrenbacher |first=Katie |work=[[GigaOm]] |date=June 11, 2009 |access-date=August 21, 2021 |archive-date=January 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220126123924/https://gigaom.com/2009/06/11/tesla-founder-eberhard-files-lawsuit-against-tesla-elon-musk/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Tesla began production of the Roadster in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ramey |first=Jay |title=The first Tesla Roadster: A look back at the early adopter's electric car |url=https://www.autoweek.com/news/green-cars/a1835876/first-tesla-roadster-look-back-early-adopters-electric-car/ |website=[[Autoweek]] |date=November 27, 2017}}</ref>

By January 2009, Tesla had raised $187&nbsp;million and delivered 147 cars. Musk had contributed $70&nbsp;million of his own money to the company.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-rise-of-elon-musk-2016-7 | title=Elon Musk's Life Story: Tesla CEO's Early Years, Career | work=[[Business Insider]] | date=June 28, 2021}}</ref>

In June 2009, Tesla was approved to receive $465&nbsp;million in interest-bearing loans from the [[United States Department of Energy]]. The funding, part of the $8&nbsp;billion [[Advanced Technology Vehicles Manufacturing Loan Program]], supported engineering and production of the Model S sedan, as well as the development of commercial powertrain technology.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2009/06/22/daily33.html | title=Tesla gets long-awaited government loan | first=Lindsay | last=Riddell | work=[[American City Business Journals]] | date=June 24, 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505192107/http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/2009/06/22/daily33.html |archive-date=May 5, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla repaid the loan in May 2013, with $12&nbsp;million interest.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cole| first=Jay |url=https://insideevs.com/news/317959/tesla-repays-entire-doe-loan-taxpayers-make-26-million-on-the-deal-updated/ |title=Tesla Repays Entire DoE Loan, Taxpayers Make $12 Million on the Deal | work=[[InsideEVs]] |date=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160506051437/http://insideevs.com/tesla-repays-entire-doe-loan-taxpayers-make-12-million-on-the-deal/ |archive-date=May 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/2013/05/22/autos/tesla-loan-repayment/index.html | title=Tesla repays federal loan nearly 10 years early | first=Chris | last=Isidore | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=May 22, 2013}}</ref>

=== IPO, Model S, and Model X (2010–2015) ===
[[File:Tesla Model S first deliveries.jpg|thumb|First deliveries of Model S at the [[Tesla Fremont Factory]] in California, in June 2012]]

In May 2010, Tesla purchased what would later become the [[Tesla Factory]] in [[Fremont, California]], from Toyota for $42&nbsp;million,<ref name=Future>{{Cite news |last=Davis |first=Joshua | title=How Elon Musk Turned Tesla into the Car Company of the Future |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/09/ff-tesla/ |url-status=live | magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |volume=18 |issue=10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624053602/http://www.wired.com/2010/09/ff_tesla/ |archive-date=June 24, 2016 |date=September 27, 2010}}</ref> and opened the facility in October 2010 to start production of the Model S.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla's Got the Factory, Now It Needs to Fill It |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/10/teslas-got-the-factory-now-it-needs-to-fill-it/ | first=Chuck | last=Squatriglia | magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | date=October 20, 2010}}</ref> On June 29, 2010, the company became a public company via an [[initial public offering]] (IPO) on [[NASDAQ]], the first American car company to do so since the [[Ford Motor Company]] had its IPO in 1956.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Matt | last=Andrejczak |title=Tesla Motors revs up $244&nbsp;million IPO |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/tesla-motors-revs-up-244-million-ipo-2010-06-28 |website=[[MarketWatch]] | date=June 28, 2010 | url-access=limited}}</ref> The company issued 13.3&nbsp;million shares of common stock at a price of $17.00 per share, raising $226&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scholer |first1=Kristen |title=Tesla Posts Second-Biggest Rally for 2010 U.S. IPO |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-06-29/tesla-motors-raises-226-million-in-first-ipo-of-u-s-carmaker-in-54-years |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |last2=Spears |first2=Lee |date=June 29, 2010 | url-access=subscription}}</ref>

In January 2012, Tesla ceased production of the Roadster, and in June the company launched its second car, the Model S luxury sedan.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Tesla Motors begins delivering Model S electric cars in a Silicon Valley milestone |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2012/06/22/tesla-motors-begins-delivering-model-s-electric-cars-in-a-silicon-valley-milestone-2/ |website=[[The Mercury News]] | date=June 22, 2012}}</ref> The Model S won several automotive awards during 2012 and 2013, including the 2013 [[Motor Trend Car of the Year]],<ref name=Award2013>{{cite news |url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/2013-motor-trend-car-of-the-year-tesla-model-s/ |title=Model S Motor Trend Car of the Year Award 2013 | first=Angus | last=MacKenzie |magazine=[[Motor Trend]] | date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> and became the first electric car to top the monthly sales ranking of a country, when it achieved first place in the Norwegian new car sales list in September 2013.<ref name="Voelcker">{{cite web |url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1087346_tesla-model-s-was-best-selling-car-in-norway-for-september |title=Tesla Model S Was Best-Selling Car in Norway For September |first=John |last=Voelcker |website=Green Car Reports |date=October 1, 2013}}</ref> The Model S was also the bestselling plug-in electric car worldwide for the years 2015 and 2016.<ref name="Top10PEVs2016" />

Tesla announced the [[Tesla Autopilot]], a driver-assistance system, in 2014. In September that year, all Tesla cars started shipping with sensors and software to support the feature, with what would later be called "hardware version 1".<ref>{{cite web| first1=K. Nived | last1=Maanyu1 | first2=D Goutham | last2=Raj | first3=R Vamsi | last3=Krishna| first4=Shruthi Bhargava | last4=Choubey | title=A Study on Tesla Autopilot |url=https://www.ijspr.com/citations/v71n1/IJSPR_7101_30573.pdf | publisher=[[Sreenidhi Institute of Science and Technology]] | date=May 2020}}</ref> In April 2015, Tesla entered the energy storage market, unveiling its [[Tesla Powerwall]] (home) and [[Tesla Powerpack]] (business) battery packs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-ceo-elon-musk-unveils-line-of-home-and-industrial-battery-packs-1430461622 |title=Tesla CEO Elon Musk Unveils Line of Home and Industrial Battery Packs |last1=Berzon |first1=Alexandra | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |last2=Sweet |first2=Cassandra| date=May 1, 2015 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> The company received orders valued at $800&nbsp;million within a week of the unveiling.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-08/tesla-s-battery-grabbed-800-million-in-its-first-week |title=Tesla's Battery Grabbed $800 Million in Its First Week |first=Tom |last=Randall |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |date=May 8, 2015 | url-access=subscription}}</ref>

Tesla began shipping its third vehicle, the luxury SUV [[Tesla Model X]], in September 2015, at which time it had 25,000 pre-orders.<ref>{{cite web |last=Logan |first=Bryan |title=Here's Tesla's first SUV, the all-electric Model X |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/here-comes-the-tesla-model-x-launch-2015-9 |website=[[Business Insider]] | date=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/2015/09/29/autos/tesla-model-x/ | title=Tesla has delivered the first Model X SUVs | first=Peter | last=Valdes-Dapena | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=September 29, 2015}}</ref>

=== SolarCity and Model 3 (2016–2018) ===
In November 2016, Tesla acquired [[SolarCity]], in an all-stock $2.6&nbsp;billion deal, and entered the [[photovoltaics]] market.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/11/21/13698314/tesla-completes-acquisition-solarcity-elon-musk | title=Tesla completes its $2.6&nbsp;billion acquisition of SolarCity | first=Andrew J. |last=Hawkins | work=[[The Verge]] | date=November 21, 2016}}</ref> The solar installation business was merged with Tesla's existing battery energy storage products division to form the Tesla Energy subsidiary.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hamilton |first=Isobel Asher |title=Elon Musk is defending Tesla's acquisition of SolarCity against angry shareholders. This is the story of how it was transformed into Tesla Energy. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/solarcity-tesla-energy-beleaguered-history-elon-musk-2021-7 |website=[[Business Insider]]| date=July 30, 2021}}</ref> The deal was controversial because at the time of the acquisition, SolarCity was facing liquidity issues of which Tesla's shareholders were not informed.<ref name="solarsue">{{cite news| last=Kolodny |first=Lora| title=Tesla's Elon Musk knew SolarCity faced a 'liquidity crisis' at time of 2016 deal, legal documents show |publisher=[[CNBC]] |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/28/musk-deposition-stockholders-v-tesla-solarcity.html |date=October 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200815214348/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/28/musk-deposition-stockholders-v-tesla-solarcity.html |archive-date=August 15, 2020}}</ref>

In February 2017, Tesla Motors changed its name to Tesla, Inc. to better reflect the scope of its expanded business, which now included electric vehicles, battery energy storage systems, and solar power generation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla is following in the footsteps of Apple and is changing its name. |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/elon-musk-s-tesla-motors-changing-its-name-n715476 | first=Robert | last=Ferris | publisher=[[CNBC]] | date=February 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/02/01/technology/tesla-name-change/ | title=Tesla Motors changes its name to ... Tesla | first=Seth | last=Fiegerman | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/2/1/14470094/tesla-motors-name-change-inc-solar | title=Tesla Motors changes company name to just Tesla | first=Sean | last=O'Kane | work=[[The Verge]] | date=February 1, 2017}}</ref>

That year Tesla also started its philanthropic effort. Tesla made multiple contributions of solar power to areas recovering from disasters in 2017, in particular installing a solar plus storage system to restore electricity at a hospital in [[Puerto Rico]], following the destruction from [[Hurricane Maria]].<ref name=philantropy1>{{cite web|title=Tesla's Philanthropic Side|url=https://www.asaproofing.com/2017/10/tesla-philanthropic-side/|website=asaproofing.com| access-date=February 6, 2019|archive-date=August 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200808104117/https://www.asaproofing.com/2017/10/tesla-philanthropic-side/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=npr_puertorico>{{cite news|title=Tesla Turns Power Back On at Children's Hospital in Puerto Rico|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/10/25/560045944/tesla-turns-power-back-on-at-childrens-hospital-in-puerto-rico|website=NPR.org|date=October 25, 2017|first=Bill |last=Chappell}}</ref> In July 2018, the company donated $37.5&nbsp;million to kindergarten to 12th grade [[STEM|science, technology, engineering, and mathematics]] education in Nevada.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rojc |first=Philip| date= July 27, 2018 | url=https://www.insidephilanthropy.com/home/2018/7/26/next-gen-whats-behind-teslas-latest-stem-education-give|title=Next Gen: What's Behind Tesla's Latest STEM Education Give?|publisher=Inside Philanthropy}}</ref>

Tesla began selling its fourth vehicle model, the Model 3 sedan, in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla hands over first Model 3 electric cars to early buyers |date=July 29, 2017 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/tesla-hands-over-first-model-3-electric-cars-early-buyers-n787716 |access-date=September 9, 2020 |publisher=NBC News |language=en}}</ref> The Model 3 was a cheaper vehicle compared to previous Tesla vehicles, and was intended for the mass market. It was highly anticipated, which prompted the company to try to speed up production.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-idUSKCN0XV2JL | title=Tesla puts pedal to the metal, 500,000 cars planned in 2018 | first1=Kshitiz | last1=Goliya | first2=Alexandria | last2=Sage | date=May 4, 2016 | work=[[Reuters]] | access-date=May 7, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507105038/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-idUSKCN0XV2JL | archive-date=May 7, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> By August 2017, there were 455,000 reservations for the Model 3.<ref name="cnn_money_reservations">{{cite news |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/02/technology/business/tesla-earnings/index.html?iid=hp-stack-dom |title=Tesla now averaging more than 1,800 Model 3 reservations a day |last1=Fiegerman |first1=Seth |date=August 3, 2017 |access-date=August 3, 2017 |work=CNN Money |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170803212821/http://money.cnn.com/2017/08/02/technology/business/tesla-earnings/index.html?iid=hp-stack-dom |archive-date=August 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rollout was plagued by delays and production problems.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/04/18/news/companies/elon-musk-tesla-model-3-production/index.html|title=Tesla will start working 24/7 to crank out Model 3s|last=Isidore|first=Chris|work=CNNMoney|access-date=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418204050/http://money.cnn.com/2018/04/18/news/companies/elon-musk-tesla-model-3-production/index.html|archive-date=April 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This increased pressure on the company, which at this time was one of the most shorted companies in the market.

In August 2018, CEO Elon Musk briefly considered taking Tesla private.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/08/07/elon-musk-tesla-private-tweet/ |title=Elon Musk tweets he's thinking about taking Tesla private | date=August 8, 2018 | work=[[TechCrunch]] | first=Megan Rose |last=Dickey}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/08/elon-musk-wants-to-take-tesla-private--heres-what-it-means.html | title=Elon Musk says he wants to take Tesla private at over $70&nbsp;billion – here's what that means | first=Tom Jr. | last=Huddleston |publisher=[[CNBC]] | date=August 8, 2018}}</ref> The plan did not materialize, and gave rise to much controversy and many lawsuits including a [[Elon Musk#SEC lawsuit|securities fraud charge from the SEC]]. By the end of 2018, the production problems had been overcome, and the Model 3 was the world's bestselling plug-in electric car for the year.<ref name="Top20Global2018">{{cite web| url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2019/01/global-top-20-december-2018.html| title=Global Top 20 – December 2018| last=Jose| first=Pontes| publisher=EVSales.com| date=January 31, 2019| access-date=February 2, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013624/http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2019/01/global-top-20-december-2018.html| archive-date=February 1, 2019| url-status=live}} "Global sales totaled 2,018,247 plug-in passenger cars in 2018, with a BEV:PHEV ratio of 69:31, and a market share of 2.1%. The world's top selling plug-in car was the Tesla Model 3, and Tesla was the top selling manufacturer of plug-in passenger cars in 2018, followed by BYD."</ref>

=== Global expansion and Model Y (2019–present) ===
Tesla opened its first "Gigafactory" outside the United States in Shanghai, China, in 2019. [[Giga Shanghai]] was the first automobile factory in China fully owned by a foreign company, and was built in less than six months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Elon Musk Set Up His Shanghai Gigafactory in Record Time |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-23/elon-musk-opened-tesla-s-shanghai-gigafactory-in-just-168-days |access-date=January 28, 2021 |work=Bloomberg.com |date=October 23, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The following year Tesla also started construction on a new Gigafactory near Berlin, Germany, and another in Texas, United States. In March 2020, Tesla began deliveries of its fifth vehicle model, the [[Tesla Model Y|Model Y]] [[crossover (automobile)|crossover]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Model Y deliveries begin: Here's what is new in Tesla's EV crossover |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2020/03/17/model-y-deliveries-begin-heres-what-is-new-in-teslas-ev-crossover/ |access-date=September 9, 2020 |website=TechCrunch |date=March 17, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref>

On January 10, 2020, Tesla reached a [[market capitalization]] of $86&nbsp;billion, breaking the record for highest valuation of any American automaker.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Isidore |title=Tesla is now the most valuable US automaker ever |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/10/investing/tesla-market-value/index.html |access-date=April 17, 2020 |publisher=CNN|date=January 10, 2020 }}</ref> On June 10, 2020, Tesla's market capitalization surpassed those of [[BMW]], [[Daimler AG|Daimler]] and [[Volkswagen]] combined.<ref>{{cite web |title=E-Autohersteller: Tesla ist wertvoller als BMW, Daimler und VW zusammen |url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/unternehmen/industrie/e-autohersteller-tesla-ist-wertvoller-als-bmw-daimler-und-vw-zusammen/25905882.html |access-date=November 25, 2020 |website=Handelsblatt |language=de}}</ref> The next month, Tesla reached a valuation of $206&nbsp;billion, surpassing [[Toyota]]'s $202&nbsp;billion to become the world's most valuable automaker by market capitalization.<ref name="Stevens-2020">{{cite web |last=Stevens |first=Pippa |date=July 1, 2020 |title=Tesla tops Toyota to become largest automaker by market value |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/07/01/tesla-tops-toyota-to-become-largest-automaker-by-market-value.html |access-date=July 1, 2020 |publisher=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> On August 31, 2020, following this increase in value, Tesla had a 5-for-1 [[stock split]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Anneken |last=Tappe |title=Apple and Tesla just announced stock splits. Here's what that means for your investments |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/08/12/investing/stock-split-apple-tesla/index.html |access-date=August 13, 2020 |publisher=CNN|date=August 12, 2020 }}</ref>

From July 2019 to June 2020, Tesla reported four profitable quarters in a row for the first time, which made it eligible for inclusion in the [[S&P 500]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kolodny |first=Lora |date=July 22, 2020 |title=Tesla reports fourth straight quarter of profits |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/07/22/tesla-tsla-earnings-q2-2020.html |access-date=July 23, 2020 |publisher=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> Tesla was added to the index on December 21, 2020.<ref name="GuardianSP500">{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Rob |title=Tesla joins Wall Street's S&P 500 share index |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/dec/21/tesla-joins-wall-streets-sp-500-share-index |access-date=December 22, 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=December 21, 2020}}</ref> It was the largest company ever added, and the sixth-largest company in the index at the time of its inclusion.<ref name=GuardianSP500 /> As investors tried to buy more shares as a result of this inclusion, some analysts, such as [[J.P. Morgan & Co.|J.P. Morgan]]'s Ryan Brinkman, suggested investors exercise caution as Tesla was "dramatically" overvalued.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla Shares Are 'Dramatically Overvalued,' JPMorgan Says|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/tesla-shares-dramatically-overvalued-jpmorgan-132603815.html|access-date=December 10, 2020|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|language=en-US}}</ref> Throughout 2020, the share price of Tesla increased 740%,<ref>{{cite web|last=Vlastelica|first=Ryan|date=January 6, 2021|title=Tesla Eyes Another Milestone as Valuation Nears Facebook's|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/tesla-eyes-another-milestone-valuation-170917947.html|access-date=January 7, 2021|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|language=en-US}}</ref> and on January 26, 2021, its market capitalization reached $848&nbsp;billion,<ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla Market Cap {{!}} TSLA|url=https://ycharts.com/companies/TSLA/market_cap|access-date=March 31, 2021|website=ycharts.com}}</ref> more than the next nine largest automakers combined and making it the 5th most valuable company in the US.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kolodny|first=Michael Wayland, Lora|date=December 14, 2020|title=Tesla's market cap tops the 9 largest automakers combined – Experts disagree about if that can last|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/12/14/tesla-valuation-more-than-nine-largest-carmakers-combined-why.html|access-date=January 7, 2021|publisher=CNBC|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bursztynsky|first=Jessica|date=January 8, 2021|title=Tesla closes day as fifth most valuable U.S. company, passing Facebook|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/07/tesla-passes-facebook-to-become-fifth-most-valuable-us-company.html|access-date=March 31, 2021|publisher=CNBC|language=en}}</ref>

From 2015 to 2020, Tesla acquired companies including Riviera Tool, [[Tesla Grohmann Automation|Grohmann Engineering]], Perbix, Compass Automation, [[Hibar Systems]], and German ATW Automation to advance Tesla's expertise in automation, along with [[Maxwell Technologies]] and SilLion to add to Tesla's abilities in battery technology.<ref>{{cite web|date=September 16, 2020|title=The Musk Method: Learn from partners then go it alone|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-batteryday-technology-insight/the-musk-method-learn-from-partners-then-go-it-alone-idUSKBN2680K4|access-date=July 9, 2021|work=Reuters|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date=October 2, 2020|title=Tesla to acquire German battery assembly maker: source|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-ats-automation-germany-idUSKBN26N2VG|access-date=October 15, 2021}}</ref> Grohmann (renamed [[Tesla Automation]]) and Maxwell would continue to operate as subsidiary companies, while the rest would be merged into Tesla. In July 2021, Musk acknowledged that Tesla had sold Maxwell to the former VP of sales for Maxwell.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kolodny|first=Lora|date=July 22, 2021|title=Elon Musk says Tesla caused two-thirds of his personal and professional pain|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/07/21/elon-musk-tesla-caused-two-thirds-of-my-personal-professional-pain.html|access-date=July 22, 2021|publisher=CNBC|language=en}}</ref>

In January 2020, Tesla donated {{currency|5&nbsp;million|CNY|linked=yes}} ($723,000 in 2020 dollars) to the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] to fight the [[COVID-19 pandemic in mainland China]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gearprimer.com/automotive/tesla-donates-5-million-yuan-to-chinese-cdc-in-fight-against-coronavirus/|title=Tesla Donates 5 Million Yuan to Chinese CDC in Fight Against Coronavirus|date=January 31, 2020|website=Gear Primer|language=en-US|access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla's Shanghai plant suspends operations amid virus outbreak|url=https://www.shine.cn/biz/auto/2001310963/|access-date=August 18, 2020|website=SHINE|language=en}}</ref>

In October 2020, Tesla told ''[[Electrek]]'' that it had dissolved its [[public relations]] (PR) department (with the exception of a few PR managers representing Tesla's European and Asian markets), becoming the first automaker to do so.<ref>{{cite web|last=Szymkowski|first=Sean|date=October 6, 2020|title=Tesla scraps whatever was left of its PR department|url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/tesla-pr-media-relations/|access-date=February 14, 2021|website=Roadshow|publisher=CNET|language=en}}</ref>

Tesla hit its goal of building 500,000 cars in 2020.<ref>{{cite news | first=Chris | last=Isidore|title=Tesla hit half-million car target in 2020 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/02/tech/tesla-2020-car-sales/index.html| date=January 2, 2021|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> The company ended the year with over $19&nbsp;billion of cash,<ref name="bb20210208" /> compared to $6.3 billion at the end of 2019.<ref name=ars20210128>{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Timothy B. |title=Tesla reports its first annual profit |url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2021/01/tesla-reports-its-first-annual-profit/ |access-date=January 28, 2021 |work=Ars Technica |date=January 27, 2021 |language=en-us}}</ref>

In February 2021, Tesla revealed that it had invested $1.5&nbsp;billion in [[bitcoin]] in 2020<ref name="bb20210208" /><ref>{{cite web|last=O'Brien|first=Sarah|date=March 24, 2021|title='You can now buy a Tesla with bitcoin,' CEO Elon Musk said. But it could mean a big tax bill|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/03/24/buying-a-tesla-using-bitcoin-it-could-mean-a-tax-bill.html|access-date=March 24, 2021|publisher=CNBC|language=en}}</ref> and on March 24 the company started accepting bitcoin as a form of payment for vehicle purchases in the United States and stated that it would introduce bitcoin payment in other countries later that year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Jon|date=March 24, 2021|title=You can now buy a Tesla with bitcoin in the US|url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/3/24/22347905/tesla-bitcoin-payment-us-cryptocurrency-elon-musk|access-date=May 14, 2021|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref> At the time, Musk tweeted that "Bitcoin paid to Tesla will be retained as Bitcoin, not converted to [[fiat currency]]."<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1374619379929772034 |user=elonmusk |title=Tesla is using only internal & open source software & operates Bitcoin nodes directly. Bitcoin paid to Tesla will be retained as Bitcoin, not converted to fiat currency. |first=Elon |last=Musk |access-date=July 22, 2021 |language=en |url=https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1374619379929772034 |via=Twitter}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Livni |first=Ephrat |date=March 24, 2021 |title=Tesla will accept Bitcoin as payment, Elon Musk says. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/24/business/elon-musk-tesla-bitcoin.html |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> It was later revealed in financial documents that between January 1 and March 31, 2021, Tesla had made a $101&nbsp;million profit on the sale of bitcoin. After 49 days of accepting the digital currency, the company reversed course on May 12, 2021, saying they would no longer take bitcoin due to concerns that "mining" the [[cryptocurrency]] was contributing to the consumption of fossil fuels and climate change.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Tesla will no longer accept Bitcoin over climate concerns, says Musk |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-57096305 | date=May 13, 2021}}</ref> The decision resulted in the price of bitcoin dropping around 12% on May 13.<ref>{{cite news|last=Iyengar|first=Rish|date=May 13, 2021|title=Bitcoin drops around 12% after Elon Musk tweets that Tesla will not accept it as payment|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/05/12/tech/elon-musk-tesla-bitcoin/index.html|access-date=May 13, 2021|publisher=CNN}}</ref> During a July bitcoin conference, Musk suggested Tesla could help bitcoin miners switch to renewable energy in the future and also stated at the same conference that if bitcoin mining reaches, and trends above 50&nbsp;percent renewable energy usage, that "Tesla would resume accepting bitcoin." The price for bitcoin rose after this announcement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elon Musk Says Tesla Likely to Accept Bitcoin Again|url=https://gizmodo.com/elon-musk-says-tesla-likely-to-accept-bitcoin-again-1847340934|access-date=July 22, 2021|website=Gizmodo|date=July 22, 2021 |language=en-us}}</ref> In July 2022 it was reported that Tesla had sold about 75% of its bitcoin holdings.<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 21, 2022 |title=Elon Musk's Tesla sells most of its Bitcoin holdings |language=en-GB |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-62246367 |access-date=July 21, 2022}}</ref> It was worth $936&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 21, 2022 |title=Tesla sells majority of its Bitcoin holdings |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/world/elon-musk-s-tesla-sells-majority-of-its-cryptocurrency-bitcoin-holdings-11658369301044.html |access-date=July 21, 2022 |website=mint |language=en}}</ref>

After earlier disputes with California officials over COVID-19 restrictions, on December 1, 2021, Tesla moved its headquarters from [[Palo Alto, California]], to its [[Giga Texas|Gigafactory]] in Austin, Texas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hull|first=Dana|date=December 1, 2021|title=Tesla Makes It Official, Marking Headquarters Move to Texas|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-01/tesla-makes-it-official-completing-headquarters-move-to-texas|access-date=December 2, 2021|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.}}</ref><ref name="Castillo-2021">{{cite web|last=Amanda del Castillo|date=October 7, 2021|title=Elon Musk says Tesla will move Palo Alto headquarters to Austin|url=https://abc7news.com/11096209/|access-date=October 13, 2021|website=ABC7 San Francisco|language=en}}</ref> However, Musk stated that Tesla would continue to operate its Fremont factory in the San Francisco Bay Area,<ref name="Castillo-2021" /> and will continue to expand in California.<ref>{{cite web|date=October 7, 2021|title=Elon Musk says Tesla will move HQ from California to Texas|url=https://apnews.com/article/technology-business-palo-alto-elon-musk-austin-7a9b375a5b69c25564c9ae4dc4fba64e|access-date=October 22, 2021|website=AP NEWS|language=en}}</ref> In September 2021, Tesla broke ground on a new battery factory in Lathrop, California,<ref>{{cite web|last=Alamalhodaei|first=Aria|date=September 23, 2021|title=Tesla's battery-manufacturing 'Megafactory' breaks ground in California|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2021/09/23/teslas-battery-manufacturing-megafactory-breaks-ground-in-california/|access-date=October 22, 2021|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US}}</ref> and signed a lease in October 2021 for additional office space in Palo Alto.<ref>{{cite web|date=October 8, 2021|title=Tesla agrees to big office lease in Palo Alto, despite HQ exit|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2021/10/08/tesla-agrees-to-big-office-lease-in-palo-alto-despite-hq-exit|access-date=October 22, 2021|website=The Mercury News|language=en-US}}</ref> Musk announced in February 2023 that Tesla would establish its global engineering headquarters in Palo Alto, moving into a corporate campus once owned by [[HP Inc.|HP]].<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Hull |first1=Dana |last2=Breslau |first2=Karen |date=2023-02-23 |title=Newsom, Musk dedicate former HP headquarters in Palo Alto to Tesla engineers |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/technology/story/2023-02-22/tesla-to-open-engineering-headquarters-in-palo-alto-california |access-date=2023-02-26 |website=Los Angeles Times |agency=Bloomberg |language=en-US}}</ref>

Also in October 2021, Tesla's market capitalization reached $1&nbsp;trillion, the sixth company to do so in U.S. history, on news that car rental company [[The Hertz Corporation|Hertz]] had placed an order for 100,000 Tesla vehicles for its fleet.<ref>{{cite news|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=October 25, 2021|title=Tesla is now worth more than $1&nbsp;trillion|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/10/25/investing/tesla-stock-trillion-dollar-market-cap/index.html|access-date=October 25, 2021|publisher=CNN}}</ref>

In March 2022, Tesla launched its new car factory outside Berlin, with Musk handing over the first deliveries to customers. Giga Berlin is the largest plant for electric vehicles in Europe.<ref name="dw.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/tesla-opens-giga-berlin-factory-in-germany/av-61210668|title=Tesla opens Giga Berlin factory in Germany|publisher=Deutsche Welle|date=March 22, 2022|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2022}}</ref> In April 2022, Tesla celebrated the public opening of the Giga Texas facility with its Cyber Rodeo event,  attended by an estimated 15,000 invitees.<ref name="auto1">{{cite news |last1=Carlson |first1=Kara |title=Inside Elon's big, weird Austin party: Music, robots – and even a petting zoo |url=https://www.statesman.com/story/business/2022/04/07/tesla-fans-show-up-cyber-rodeo-celebration-austin/9504356002/ |access-date=April 9, 2022 |publisher=Austin American-Statesman |date=April 7, 2022}}</ref>

In June 2022, Musk said in an email sent to employees that he was reducing salaried headcount by 10&nbsp;percent because the company had become "overstaffed in many areas", adding that "hourly headcount will increase." He also said in a tweet Tesla's total number of employees would increase over the next year, but said the number of salaried staff would remain "fairly flat".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/news-by-subject/technology/3512199-musk-says-tesla-headcount-will-increase/ |title= Musk says Tesla headcount will increase |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=June 5, 2022 }}</ref>

In August 2022, Musk claimed that Tesla had made more than 3 million cars.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Leswing |first=Kif |title=Elon Musk says Tesla has made over 3 million cars |date=August 14, 2022 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/08/14/elon-musk-says-tesla-has-made-over-3-million-cars.html |access-date=August 14, 2022 |publisher=CNBC |language=en}}</ref>

In 2023, Tesla had to pause plans to double Giga Shanghai production to 2 million cars per year after encountering roadblocks from the [[Government of China|Chinese central government]]. Officials there expressed concerns with Elon's activities at [[SpaceX]], in particular the quickly expanding [[Starlink#Military capabilities|military applications of Starlink]] and its potential impact on global strategic defense.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-01-12/tesla-china-factory-expansion-plans-in-doubt-amid-data-concerns |title=Tesla China Plant Expansion in Doubt Over Starlink Concerns |work=Bloomberg |location=US |date=2023-01-12 |access-date=2023-01-21}}</ref>

In March 2023, Musk announced that the next Gigafactory will be constructed in [[Monterrey|Monterrey, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theverge.com/2023/3/1/23571725/tesla-gigafactory-monterrey-mexico-announce-investor-day |title=Tesla confirms its next Gigafactory will be in Mexico |date=March 1, 2023 |website=The Verge |last=Shakir |first=Umar}}</ref>

== Automotive products ==
{{redirect-distinguish|Tesla electric car|Nikola Tesla electric car hoax}}
{{As of|2022|December}}, Tesla offers four car models: Model S, Model X, Model 3 and Model Y, and a [[Tesla Semi|semi-truck]]. Tesla's first vehicle, the [[Tesla Roadster (first generation)|first-generation Tesla Roadster]], is no longer sold. Tesla has plans for a [[Tesla Roadster (second generation)|second-generation Roadster]] and a pickup called the [[Tesla Cybertruck|Cybertruck]].

=== In production ===
==== Model S ====
{{Main|Tesla Model S}}
[[File:2018 Tesla Model S 75D.jpg|thumb|Tesla Model S]]

The Model S is a five-door [[liftback]] [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]]. Deliveries began on June 22, 2012.<ref name="1stModelS">{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_20919722/silicon-valley-milestone-tesla-motors-begins-delivering-model |title=In a Silicon Valley milestone, Tesla Motors begins delivering Model S electric cars |last=Boudreau |first=John |work=[[Mercury News]] |date=June 22, 2012 |access-date=June 22, 2012}}</ref> The car became the first electric vehicle to top the monthly sales ranking in any country, when it achieved first place in the Norwegian new car sales list in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gronnbil.no/nyheter/norges-mest-solgte-bil-i-september-er-en-elbil-article352-239.html |title=Norges mest solgte bil i september er en elbil |language=no |trans-title=Norway's best selling car in September is an electric vehicle |work=Grønn bil |date=October 1, 2013 |access-date=October 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215426/http://www.gronnbil.no/nyheter/norges-mest-solgte-bil-i-september-er-en-elbil-article352-239.html |archive-date=October 4, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Voelcker" /> The Model S won the 2013 [[Motor Trend Car of the Year]],<ref name=Award2013 /> the 2013 "[[World Green Car]]",<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/press-release/20130328/now-there-one-tesla-model-s-declared-2013-world-green-car-1158695# |title=And Now There Is One.... Tesla Model S Declared 2013 World Green Car [press release] |agency=PR Newswire |newspaper=[[International Business Times]] |date=March 28, 2013 |access-date=March 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130524082052/http://www.ibtimes.com/press-release/20130328/now-there-one-tesla-model-s-declared-2013-world-green-car-1158695 |archive-date=May 24, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Automobile (magazine)|Automobile]]'' magazine's 2013 "Car of the Year",<ref>{{cite web |last=Zenlea |first=David |title=2013 Automobile of the Year: Tesla Model S |url=http://www.automobilemag.com/features/awards/1301_2013_automobile_of_the_year_tesla_model_s/ |magazine=[[Automobile (magazine)|Automobile]] |date=November 1, 2012 |access-date=November 1, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's Best 25 Inventions of the Year 2012 award,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://techland.time.com/2012/11/01/best-inventions-of-the-year-2012/slide/the-tesla-model-s/ |title=Best Inventions of the Year 2012{{snd}}$22,000 – $750,000{{snd}}The Tesla Model S |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=November 1, 2012}}</ref> as well as the 2019 ''Motor Trend'' "Ultimate Car of the Year".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/2013-tesla-model-s-beats-chevy-toyota-cadillac-ultimate-car-of-the-year/ |title=Tesla Model S Beats Chevy, Toyota, and Cadillac for Ultimate Car of the Year Honors |access-date=January 2, 2020 |magazine=[[Motor Trend]]|date=July 10, 2019 }}</ref>

The Model S was the bestselling plug-in electric car worldwide for the years 2015 and 2016, selling an estimated 50,931 units in 2016.<ref name="Top10PEVs2016">{{cite news |url=http://www.hybridcars.com/tesla-model-s-is-worlds-best-selling-plug-in-car-for-second-year-in-a-row/ |title=Tesla Model S Is World's Best-Selling Plug-in Car For Second Year in a Row |first=Jeff |last=Cobb |website=HybridCars.com |date=January 26, 2017 |access-date=January 31, 2017}}</ref> By the end of 2017, it was the world's second bestselling plug-in electric car in history (after the [[Nissan Leaf]]), with global sales of 200,000 units.<ref name="ModelS200k">{{cite news |url=http://www.hybridcars.com/tesla-quietly-sold-200000th-model-s-last-year/ |title=Tesla Quietly Sold 200,000th Model S Last Year |first=Jeff |last=Cobb |work=HybridCars.com |date=January 22, 2018 |access-date=January 22, 2018}} "Tesla sold its 200,000 Model S in the fourth quarter of 2017, in October or early November, becoming the second plug-in car to cross this sales threshold after the Nissan Leaf (300,000 units by early 2017). {{As of|2017|12}}, Tesla reported global sales of 212,874 Model S cars."</ref> In June 2020, Tesla announced that the Model S Long Range Plus had an [[FTP-75|EPA range]] of {{Convert|402|miles|km|abbr=}}, the highest of any [[battery electric vehicle]] at the time.<ref>{{cite web|date=June 16, 2020|title=Tesla Model S Long Range Plus Exceeds 400 Miles Of Range, EPA Confirms|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/06/16/tesla-model-s-long-range-plus-exceeds-400-miles-of-range-epa-confirms/|access-date=October 6, 2020|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US}}</ref>

{{clear}}

==== Model X ====
{{Main|Tesla Model X}}
[[File:2017 Tesla Model X 100D Front.jpg|thumb|Tesla Model X]]

The Tesla Model X is a [[mid-size]] [[crossover SUV]]. It is offered in 5-, 6- and 7-passenger configurations. The Model X was developed from the [[Full-size car|full-sized sedan]] platform of the Model S. The rear passenger doors open vertically with an articulating "falcon-wing" design.

Deliveries started in September 2015.<ref name="cnbc20150903">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/09/03/tesla-signature-series-model-x-to-begin-delivery-september-29.html|title=Tesla Signature series Model X to begin delivery September 29|date=September 3, 2015|access-date=September 4, 2015|publisher=CNBC|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> In 2016, after one full year on the market, the Model X ranked seventh among the world's bestselling plug-in cars.<ref name="Top10PEVs2016" /> The United States is its main market, with an estimated 57,327 units sold through September 2018.<ref name="SalesUS_InsideEVs">{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/news/343998/monthly-plug-in-ev-sales-scorecard/ |title=Final Update: Quarterly Plug-In EV Sales Scorecard |publisher=[[InsideEVs]] |first=Steven |last=Loveday |date=January 17, 2020 |access-date=August 21, 2021 |archive-date=April 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419234131/https://insideevs.com/monthly-plug-in-sales-scorecard/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==== Model 3 ====
{{Main|Tesla Model 3}}
[[File:2019 Tesla Model 3 Performance AWD Front.jpg|thumb|Tesla Model 3]]

The Model 3 is a four-door [[fastback]] sedan. Tesla unveiled the Model 3 on March 31, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|date=March 31, 2016|title=Tesla Model 3: Elon Musk unveils the Model 3 to huge fanfare|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/autos/la-fi-hy-tesla-model-3-20160331-htmlstory.html|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Potential customers began reserving spots earlier that day with a refundable deposit.<ref>{{cite web|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=April 1, 2016|title=Tesla got 200,000 orders for the Model 3 in about one day|url=https://money.cnn.com/2016/04/01/news/companies/tesla-model-3-stock-price/index.html|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=CNNMoney}}</ref> One week after the unveiling, Tesla reported over 325,000 reservations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hull|first=Dana|date=April 7, 2016|title=Tesla Says It Received More Than 325,000 Model 3 Reservations|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-07/tesla-says-model-3-pre-orders-surge-to-325-000-in-first-week|access-date=April 16, 2016}}</ref> [[Bloomberg News]] claimed that, due to the number of reservations, "the Model 3's unveiling was unique in the 100-year history of the mass-market automobile."<ref>{{cite news|last=Randall|first=Tom|date=April 21, 2016|title=Ten Charts That Will Make You Rethink Tesla's Model 3|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-21/tesla-changed-cars-forever-now-it-must-deliver|access-date=May 7, 2016}}</ref> Limited vehicle production began in July 2017.<ref name="Tesla4Q2016final">{{cite web|date=February 22, 2017|title=Tesla Fourth Quarter & Full Year 2016 Update|url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x929284/22C29259-6C19-41AC-9CAB-899D148F323D/TSLA_Update_Letter_2016_4Q.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223212145/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x929284/22C29259-6C19-41AC-9CAB-899D148F323D/TSLA_Update_Letter_2016_4Q.pdf|archive-date=February 23, 2017|access-date=February 22, 2017|work=Tesla Inc.|location=Palo Alto}} ''Production totaled 24,882 vehicles in 4Q 2016 and vehicle deliveries totaled 22,252 units. No breakdown by model was provided.''</ref>

Since March 2020, the Model 3 is the world's bestselling electric car in history, and cumulative global sales passed the 1&nbsp;million milestone in June 2021.<ref name=1miModel3>{{cite web|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2021/08/26/tesla-model-3-has-passed-1-million-sales/ |title=Tesla Model 3 Has Passed 1 Million Sales |first=Zachary |last=Shahan |publisher=CleanTechnica |date=August 26, 2021 |access-date=August 26, 2021}}</ref><ref name="Model3TopEV">{{cite news|last=Holland|first=Maximilian|date=February 10, 2020|title=Tesla Passes 1 Million EV Milestone & Model 3 Becomes All Time Best Seller|website=CleanTechnica|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/03/10/tesla-passes-1-million-ev-milestone-and-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-seller/|url-status=live|access-date=May 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200412045911/https://cleantechnica.com/2020/03/10/tesla-passes-1-million-ev-milestone-and-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-seller/|archive-date=April 12, 2020|quote=Tesla's quarterly reports, meanwhile, had put the Model 3's cumulative sales at 447,980 at the end of 2019.}}</ref><ref name="Top20Global2020">{{cite web|last=Jose|first=Pontes|date=February 2, 2021|title=Global Top 20 – December 2020|url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2021/02/global-top-20-december-2020.html|access-date=February 3, 2021|publisher=EVSales.com}} "Global sales totaled 3,124,793 plug-in passenger cars in 2020, with a BEV to PHEV ratio of 69:31, and a global market share of 4%. The world's top selling plug-in car was the Tesla Model 3 with 365,240 units delivered, and Tesla was the top selling manufacturer of plug-in passenger cars in 2019 with 499,535 units, followed by VW with 220,220."</ref> The Model 3 has ranked as the world's bestselling [[plug-in electric car]] for four consecutive years, from 2018 to 2021,<ref name="Top20Global2020" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Kane|first1=Sean|date=February 22, 2019|title=Tesla's Model 3 was the best-selling EV in the world last year|language=en|work=The Verge|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/22/18236707/tesla-model-3-2018-best-selling-ev-global|access-date=February 1, 2021}}</ref><ref name="GlobalTopEVs2021">{{cite web|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2022/01/30/world-ev-sales-tesla-model-3-wins-4th-consecutive-best-seller-title-in-record-year/ | title=World EV Sales – Tesla Model 3 Wins 4th Consecutive Best Seller Title in Record Year | last=Jose | first=Pontes | publisher=CleanTechnica| date=January 30, 2022 | access-date=February 5, 2022}} "The top 3 global best selling plug-in electric cars in 2021 were the Tesla Model 3 (500,713), the Wuling Hongguang Mini EV (424,138), and the Tesla Model Y (410,517)"</ref> and also as the bestselling plug-in electric car in the United States since 2018.<ref name="TopUS2018">{{cite web|last=Kane|first=Mark|date=January 24, 2019|title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: December 2018|url=https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-december-2018/|access-date=January 24, 2019|publisher=InsideEVs.com}} ''See Graph: "Top 10 U.S. Plug-in cars (cumulative sales)" and "U.S. Plug-in Car Sales (cumulative)"''</ref><ref name="Top3US022019">{{cite web|last=Kane|first=Mark|date=March 12, 2019|title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: February 2019|url=https://insideevs.com/us-electric-car-sales-charted-february-2019/|access-date=March 12, 2019|publisher=InsideEVs.com}}</ref><ref name="TopEVs2020US">{{cite news|first=C.J. |last=Moore|date=February 14, 2021|title=Tesla's commanding lead in U.S. EVs illustrated by registration report|work=[[Automotive News]]|publisher=CarAdvice|url=https://www.caradvice.com.au/924717/proof-electric-cars-dont-need-taxpayer-support-tesla-and-gm-sales-up-despite-running-out-of-7500-tax-credits/|access-date=February 14, 2021}} ''According to [[Experian]], in 2020 the top U.S. EVs by registrations were the Tesla Model 3 (95,135), Tesla Model Y (71,344), Chevrolet Bolt EV (19,664), the Tesla Model X (19,652), Tesla Model S (14,430) and the Nissan Leaf (8,972). All four Tesla models accounted for 200,561 registrations, up 16% from 2019.''</ref> The Model 3 also set records in Norway and the Netherlands, as the bestselling passenger car model in those countries in 2019.<ref name="TopOverallSales">{{cite web|last=Shahan|first=Zachary|date=January 19, 2020|title=Tesla Model 3 = #1 Best Selling Auto in Netherlands & Norway in 2019|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/01/19/tesla-model-3-1-best-selling-automobile-in-netherlands-norway-in-2019/|access-date=May 16, 2020|work=Clean Technica|quote=In Norway and the Netherlands, the Model 3 was the #1 best selling automobile of any kind in any class in 2019.}}</ref><ref name="OFV2019Modell">{{cite web|publisher=Norwegian Road Federation (OFV)|date=January 2020|title=OFV Registreringsstatistikk|trans-title=OFV Registration Statistics|url=https://ofv.no/registreringsstatistikk|access-date=May 10, 2020|language=no}}'' To access the sales ranking by model choose "Modell" and the tabs for "2019" and "Desember" – The Tesla Model 3 was the best selling passenger car in Norway in 2019 with 15,683 units registered.''</ref>

==== Model Y ====
{{Main|Tesla Model Y}}
[[File:2020 Tesla Model Y, front 8.1.20.jpg|thumb|Tesla Model Y]]

The Model Y is a [[Compact car|compact]] [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover utility vehicle]]. The Model Y is built on a platform that shares many components with the Model 3.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/2/17313026/tesla-model-y-elon-musk-production-manufacturing-revolution|title=Elon Musk says Tesla Model Y will be a 'manufacturing revolution'|date=May 3, 2018|work=The Verge|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The car has up to three rows of seats (up to 7 people),<ref>{{cite web|date=January 10, 2021|title=Tesla Model Y's Optional Third Row Is Ultra-Tiny|url=https://carbuzz.com/news/tesla-model-ys-optional-third-row-is-ultra-tiny|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=CarBuzz|language=en-us}}</ref> {{Convert|68|cuft}} of cargo space (with the second and third rows folded),<ref>{{cite web|date=May 26, 2020|title=Tesla Model Y Interior Review|url=https://www.motortrend.com/reviews/tesla-model-y-interior-review/|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=MotorTrend|language=en}}</ref> and has an EPA range of up to {{Convert|326|miles|km|abbr=}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=2021 Tesla Model Y Long Range AWD|url=https://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/Find.do?action=sbs&id=43406|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=fueleconomy.gov}}</ref>

The Model Y was unveiled on March 14, 2019.<ref name="Lambert">{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2019/03/14/tesla-model-y-electric-suv-unveil/|title=Tesla unveils Model Y electric SUV with 300 miles range and 7-seats|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=March 15, 2019|website=Electrek|language=en-US|access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> Deliveries for the Model Y started on March 13, 2020. The Tesla Model Y is being manufactured at Tesla Factory in Fremont, California,<ref name="Bloomberg">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-02/musk-says-tesla-is-likely-to-produce-model-y-in-fremont |title=Musk Says Tesla Is Likely to Produce Model Y in Fremont |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. |date=June 2, 2019 |access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> as well as in Giga Shanghai in China. Giga Berlin produces the Performance, AWD and RWD versions of the Model Y.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-germany-base-model-y-more-demand-price-cuts/ |title=Tesla Germany's base Model Y gets longer delivery estimate after price cuts |first=Maria |last=Merano |work=Teslarati |date=2023-01-19 |access-date=2023-01-23}}</ref>

==== Tesla Semi ====
{{Main|Tesla Semi}}
[[File:Tesla Semi 3.jpg|thumb|Tesla Semi]]

The Tesla Semi is an all-electric [[Class 8 truck|Class 8]] [[semi-trailer truck]] announced in November 2017. Musk confirmed that two variants would be available: one with {{convert|300|miles|km|abbr=out|round=10}} and one with {{convert|500|miles|km|abbr=out|round=10}} of range.<ref>{{Cite web |date=November 14, 2017 |title=Tesla's entry into truck-making presents a whole new challenge for Elon Musk |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-hy-tesla-truck-preview-20171114-story.html |access-date=September 1, 2022 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US}}</ref> The Semi will be powered by four independent electric motors of the type used in the [[Tesla Model 3]] and will include an extensive set of hardware sensors to enable it to stay in its own lane, a safe distance away from other vehicles, and later, when software and regulatory conditions allow, provide [[self-driving car|self-driving]] operation on highways.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-truck-revealed/ |title=Elon Musk Reveals Tesla's Electric Semitruck|last=Davies|first=Alex |date=November 16, 2017|magazine=Wired|access-date=February 3, 2018|location=US}}</ref> Musk also announced that the company would be involved in installing a solar-powered global network of [[Tesla Megacharger]]s to make the Semi more attractive to potential long-haul customers. A 30-minute charge would provide {{Convert|400|miles|km|abbr=out|round=10}} of range.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/tesla-electric-truck-walmart-test-1.4407198 |title=Loblaw, Walmart to test out Tesla's all-electric Semi in Canada|last=Sage|first=Alexandria |date=November 17, 2017|publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 15, 2018|location=Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/teslas-electric-semi-truck-gets-orders-from-wal-mart-and-j-b-hunt-1510950438 |title=Tesla's Electric Semi Truck Gets Orders From Wal-Mart and J.B. Hunt|last=Smith|first=Jennifer |date=November 17, 2017|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=April 15, 2018|location=US}}</ref>

Musk initially said in 2017 that Semi deliveries would start in 2019 and be selling 100,000 trucks a year, but deliveries were later delayed to 2021 and then 2022.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Babcock |first1=Stephane |title=Tesla Announces Semi to Hit in 2023 |url=https://www.act-news.com/news/musk-tesla-semi-to-hit-in-2023/ |website=ACT News |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20211021053941/https://www.act-news.com/news/musk-tesla-semi-to-hit-in-2023/ |archive-date=October 21, 2021 |date=October 20, 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> Part of the reason for the delays, according to Musk, is that the Semi includes five times more battery cells than their passenger cars, and the battery supply is not yet sufficient for both Tesla cars and the Semi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla delays Semi production and deliveries until 2021|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/29/tesla-delays-semi-production-and-deliveries-until-2021.html|last=Kolodny |first=Lora |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=April 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Somerville| first=Heather |title=Tesla's Delayed Semi Truck Tests Elon Musk's Ability to Scale Up |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/teslas-delayed-semi-truck-tests-elon-musks-ability-to-scale-up-11606568448 |date=November 28, 2020 |issn=0099-9660 | url-access=subscription}}</ref>

In October 2022, the company announced it would deliver its first all-electric semitrailer truck for [[PepsiCo]] in December, in what would be the first new model the company would give to consumers since the beginning of 2020, when it started delivering the Model Y crossover. At the time of the announcement, the trucks would support PepsiCo plants in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] and [[Modesto, California|Modesto]], California.<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 7, 2022 |title=Tesla to Deliver Its First Electric Semi Trucks to Pepsi 3 Years Late |url=https://gizmodo.com/elon-musk-tesla-semi-truck-pepsi-delivered-late-1849629540 |access-date=December 1, 2022 |website=Gizmodo |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=DiNapoli |first1=Jessica |last2=Kumar |first2=Uday Sampath |last3=DiNapoli |first3=Jessica |date=October 7, 2022 |title=PepsiCo confirms Tesla Semi truck deliveries to start in December |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/pepsico-confirms-tesla-semi-truck-deliveries-start-december-2022-10-07/ |access-date=December 1, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Elliott |first=Rebecca |title=Tesla Set to Deliver Semi Truck to PepsiCo, Expanding Beyond Passenger Vehicles |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-set-to-deliver-semi-truck-to-pepsico-expanding-beyond-passenger-vehicles-11669899360 |access-date=December 1, 2022 |website=The Wall Street Journal |date=December 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Future products ===
==== Roadster (second generation) ====
{{Main|Tesla Roadster (second generation)}}
[[File:Tesla roadster 2020 prototype.jpg|thumb|Tesla Roadster prototype]]

In a surprise reveal at the end of the event that introduced the [[Tesla Semi]] on November 16, 2017, Tesla unveiled the second generation Roadster. Musk said that the new model will have a range of {{Convert|620|mi}} with the {{Convert|200|kWh}} battery pack and will achieve {{Convert|0–60|mph}} in 1.9 seconds; it also will achieve {{Convert|0–100|mph}} in 4.2 seconds,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1113862_tesla-roadster-is-back-0-60-in-1-9-seconds-620-mile-range|title=Tesla Roadster is back: 0–60 in 1.9 seconds, 620-mile range|website=Green Car Reports|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> and the top speed will be over {{convert|250|mph|abbr=out}}. The [[SpaceX]] Package will include cold air thrusters that will increase the speed even more.<ref name="Gibbs">{{cite news|last=Gibbs|first=Samuel|date=November 17, 2017|title=Tesla Roadster: nine things we know about the 'smackdown to gasoline cars'|newspaper=The Guardian|location=UK|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/nov/17/tesla-roadster-electric-supercar-elon-musk-fast|access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref> The vehicle will have three electric motors allowing for [[all-wheel drive]] and [[torque vectoring]] during cornering.<ref name="Gibbs" />

At the time, the base price was set at $200,000, while the first 1,000 units (the Founder's series) will sell for $250,000.<ref name="Gibbs" /> Reservations required a deposit of $50,000, and those who ordered the Founder's series paid the $250,000 in full upon ordering. Those who made a reservation at the event were allowed a test drive (with a driver) in the prototype.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-tesla-model-s-just-got-upgraded-to-ludicrous-speed-1718577723 |title=The Tesla Model S Just Got Upgraded to Ludicrous Speed |first=Michael |last=Ballaban |date=July 17, 2015 |access-date=July 22, 2015 |website=[[Jalopnik]]}}</ref> Deliveries are expected to start in 2023.<ref>{{cite web|date=September 1, 2021|title=Elon Musk: Tesla Roadster Delayed (Again), This Time to 2023|url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-roadster-delayed-again-2023-elon-musk-twitter/|access-date=September 3, 2021|website=MotorTrend|language=en|archive-date=September 3, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210903004810/https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-roadster-delayed-again-2023-elon-musk-twitter/|url-status=live}}</ref>

{{clear}}

==== Cybertruck ====
{{Main|Tesla Cybertruck}}
[[File:Tesla Cybertruck outside unveil modified by Smnt.jpg|thumb|right|Tesla Cybertruck]]

The Cybertruck is a [[pickup truck]] unveiled on November 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Kane|first1=Sean |date=November 21, 2019|title=Elon Musk just announced the new Tesla Cybertruck|language=en|work=The Verge|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/21/20975475/tesla-cybertruck-announcement-musk-electric-truck-pickup-features-range-price-release-date}}</ref> Production has been delayed past 2022, and {{As of|2023|February|lc=y}} it is scheduled to be Mid 2023.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jin|first=Hyunjoo|date=January 14, 2022|title=Exclusive: Tesla delays initial production of Cybertruck to early 2023 – source|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/exclusive-tesla-delays-initial-production-cybertruck-early-2023-source-2022-01-13/|access-date=January 30, 2022}}</ref> The truck's design had a mixed reception, and some Wall Street analysts questioned whether American pickup truck buyers will have interest in the Cybertruck.<ref>{{Cite news|date=November 22, 2019|title=Shattered glass: Futuristic design questioned after Tesla Cybertruck launch|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-truck-windows-idUSKBN1XW1CU|access-date=May 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ricker|first=Thomas|date=November 22, 2019|title=Elon Musk's Cybertruck is here, and so are the jokes|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/22/20975725/love-hate-telsa-cybertruck-design|access-date=May 13, 2020|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Matt |last=McFarland|title=Tesla's Cybertruck has become the butt of every internet joke|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/22/tech/cybertruck-tesla-pickup-truck-jokes/index.html|access-date=May 13, 2020|publisher=CNN|date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> On September 22, 2020, Musk revealed roughly 600,000 Cybertruck preorders.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Szymkowski|first1=Sean|title=Tesla Battery Day recap: Major announcements include Model S Plaid and a $25,000 EV|language=en|work=Roadshow|publisher=[[CNET]]|url=https://www.cnet.com/roadshow/news/tesla-battery-day-model-s-plaid-cybertruck-elon-musk/}}</ref> James Goodwin, chief executive of [[Australasian New Car Assessment Program|ANCAP]], said in 2019 that the design of the Cybertruck could pose safety risks, saying that the front "would look like it's not very forgiving".<ref>{{cite web|last=Schmidt|first=Bridie|date=November 27, 2019|title=Tesla Cybertruck may be unsafe for other road users, says Australian safety chief|url=https://thedriven.io/2019/11/27/tesla-cybertruck-may-be-unsafe-for-other-road-users-says-australian-safety-chief/|access-date=May 13, 2020|website=The Driven|language=en-US}}</ref> After the Cybertruck's unveiling, Musk announced that the [[Tesla Cyberquad]], an electric four-wheel [[quad bike]] revealed alongside the Cybertruck, would be an optional accessory for Cybertruck buyers.<ref>{{cite news |first=R. | last= Lawler|title=Elon Musk confirms Tesla's 'Cyberquad' as a Cybertruck accessory |url=https://www.engadget.com/2019-11-22-cyberquad-electric-atv-cybertruck-tesla.html |work=[[Engadget]] |date=November 23, 2019}}</ref>

====Tesla next-generation vehicle====
{{Main|Tesla next-generation vehicle}}

The [[Tesla next-generation vehicle]] is an upcoming battery electric car under development by Tesla as of 2022. The unnamed next-generation vehicle will be the third mainstream [[Car platform|platform]] for the company and Musk has claimed that its production volumes will greatly surpass those of the Model 3/Y platform, which would happen no earlier than 2025 according to ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref name=forbes20230107>{{cite news |title=Tesla Next Generation Platform: Everything We Know So Far |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamesmorris/2023/01/07/tesla-next-generation-platform-everything-we-know-so-far/?sh=5470a0d827aa |last=Morris|first=James |work=[[Forbes]] |date=7 January 2023 |access-date=13 March 2023}}</ref>

{{clear}}

=== Discontinued ===
==== Tesla Roadster ====
{{Main|Tesla Roadster (first generation)}}
[[File:Tesla Roadster Japanese display.jpg|thumb|The original Roadster]]
The only discontinued Tesla vehicle model is the original Tesla Roadster.<ref name="Sales0611">{{cite news|last=Woodyard|first=Chris|date=August 3, 2011|title=Tesla boasts about electric car deliveries, plans for sedan|work=[[USA Today]]|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/driveon/post/2011/08/tesla-boasts-about-electric-car-deliveries-plans-for-sedan/1|access-date=October 4, 2011}}</ref> The Roadster was a two-seater sports car, evolved from the [[Lotus Elise]] chassis,<ref>{{cite web|date=July 11, 2005|title=Supply Agreement for Products and Services – Lotus Cars Limited|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1318605/000119312510017054/dex1023.htm|website=sec.gov}}</ref> that was produced from 2008 to 2012. The Roadster was the first highway legal serial production all-electric car to use lithium-ion battery cells and the first production all-electric car to travel more than {{convert|320|km|miles|abbr=out|round=10|order=flip}} per charge. It is also the first production car to be [[Elon Musk's Tesla Roadster|launched into space]]; Musk launched his Roadster into a Mars-crossing orbit on a SpaceX [[Falcon Heavy]] rocket [[Falcon Heavy test flight|test flight]] on February 6, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Plait|first1=Phil|date=December 2, 2017|title=Elon Musk: On the Roadster to Mars|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/elon-musk-on-the-roadster-to-mars|access-date=December 8, 2017|website=Syfy}}</ref>

=== Other concepts ===
On July 20, 2016, Musk detailed his new master plan "part deux" for Tesla. It includes more affordable cars produced in higher volume, solar roofs, mid-size vehicles, SUVs and pickup trucks, as well as the refinement of autonomous vehicles and the creation of a [[sharing economy]], in which cars can be active while the owner is not using them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/07/20/tesla-motors-ceo-releases-new-master-plan.html|title=Musk Sees Tesla's Future: Trucks, Transit and Solar in a Push to Sustainability|last1=Ferris|first1=Robert|date=July 20, 2016|publisher=CNBC|access-date=July 22, 2016}}</ref> Tesla's plan also indicated building a minibus on the Model X platform,<ref>{{cite web|title=Elon Musk Confirms Tesla Minibus Built on Model X Chassis|url=https://fortune.com/2016/07/31/elon-musk-tesla-minibus-2017/|access-date=April 7, 2021|website=Fortune|language=en}}</ref> but in May 2017, Musk indicated that he might favor a 10–12 passenger version of the Model X over a dedicated minibus design.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=May 3, 2017|title=Elon Musk hints Tesla may not build a bus after all|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/3/15537926/tesla-bus-project-electric-elon-musk|access-date=April 7, 2021|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref> Musk dashed hopes for a Tesla motorcycle, saying in 2018 "we're not going to do motorcycles".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gastelu|first1=Gary|date=June 6, 2018|title=Elon Musk was almost killed on a motorcycle, so Tesla will never build them|publisher=Fox News|url=http://www.foxnews.com/auto/2018/06/06/tesla-will-never-build-motorcycles-because-elon-musk-was-almost-killed-on-one.html|access-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref>

Also in 2016, Musk revealed Tesla's intention to produce a car cheaper than the Model 3.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mearian|first=Lucas|date=April 27, 2016|title=Elon Musk says Tesla's next-gen Model 4 will be affordable for everyone|url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/3062365/elon-musk-says-teslas-next-gen-model-4-will-be-affordable-for-everyone.html|access-date=October 8, 2020|website=Computerworld|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, Musk indicated a plan to enter a new market segment, offering a compact hatchback in "less than five years".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/tesla-compact-hatchback-launch-within-five-years|title=Tesla compact hatchback to launch within five years|last1=Beckwith|first1=Jimi|date=June 6, 2018|work=Autocar|access-date=June 12, 2018|location=UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.carscoops.com/2018/06/tesla-launch-new-compact-ev-less-five-years/|title=Tesla Could Launch A New Compact EV In Less Than Five Years|last1=Anderson|first1=Brad|date=June 9, 2018|work=Carscoops|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> In 2020, Musk said Tesla expects to have a $25,000 electric car within 3 years, which "will basically be on-par or slightly better than a comparable gasoline car".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chokshi|first=Niraj|date=September 22, 2020|title=Elon Musk Promises to Make a $25,000 Tesla (in 3 Years)|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/09/22/business/tesla-elon-musk-battery-day.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200923011543/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/09/22/business/tesla-elon-musk-battery-day.html |archive-date=September 23, 2020 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=October 8, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

In April 2019, Musk announced Tesla's intention to launch an [[autonomous taxi]] service by the end of 2020 using more than 1 million Tesla vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/04/elon-musk-robot-taxis-replace-uber-and-lyft|title=Elon Musk Wants His Own 'Robot Taxis' to Replace Uber and Lyft|last=Durkee|first=Alison|website=The Hive|date=April 23, 2019|language=en|access-date=April 23, 2019}}</ref> A year later, in April 2020, Musk stated Tesla would not make the end of 2020 deadline but said, "we'll have the functionality necessary for full self-driving by the end of the year."<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Mike|title=Tesla robo-taxi release date: Elon Musk outlines 3-step plan|url=https://www.inverse.com/innovation/tesla-robo-taxi-elon-musk-gives-updated-timeline|access-date=October 8, 2020|website=Inverse|date=May 8, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>

== Tesla Energy products ==
{{Main|Tesla Energy}}
[[File:Johnstone 000178 172617 517894 4578 (36736411886).jpg|thumb|200px|Two Tesla Powerwall 2 home energy storage devices from Tesla Energy]]

Tesla subsidiary Tesla Energy develops, builds, sells and installs [[Photovoltaics|solar energy generation]] systems and battery energy storage products (as well as related products and services) to residential, commercial and industrial customers.

The subsidiary was created by the merger of Tesla's existing battery energy storage products division with SolarCity, a solar energy company that Tesla acquired in 2016.<ref name="Desjardins 2018">{{Cite news|last=Desjardins|first=Jeff|date=April 28, 2018|title=Here's what the future of Tesla could look like|work=[[Business Insider]]|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/heres-what-the-future-of-tesla-could-look-like-2018-4|url-status=live|access-date=January 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501203935/https://www.businessinsider.com/heres-what-the-future-of-tesla-could-look-like-2018-4|archive-date=May 1, 2018}}</ref>

Tesla Energy's generation products include solar panels (built by other companies for Tesla), the Tesla Solar Roof (a [[solar shingle]] system) and the Tesla Solar Inverter. Other products include the [[Tesla Powerwall|Powerwall]] (a [[home energy storage]] device) and the [[Tesla Powerpack|Powerpack]] and [[Tesla Megapack|Megapack]], which are large-scale energy storage systems.<ref name="Hanley 2016">{{Cite news|last=Hanley|first=Steve|date=August 12, 2016|title=Elon Musk & SolarCity CTO Peter Rive Announce 'Solar Roof' (Not 'Solar on the Roof')|language=en-US|work=CleanTechnica|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2016/08/12/elon-musk-solarcity-cto-peter-rive-announce-solar-roof-not-solar-roof/|access-date=May 12, 2021}}</ref><ref name="Solar Reviews 2021">{{Cite news|date=May 9, 2021|title=Complete review of Tesla solar panels: are they worth it?|language=en|work=Solar Reviews|url=https://www.solarreviews.com/blog/are-tesla-solar-panels-worth-it|access-date=May 12, 2021}}</ref><ref name="Debord 20152">{{Cite news|last=Debord|first=Matthew|date=May 1, 2015|title=Elon Musk's big announcement: it's called 'Tesla Energy'|work=[[Business Insider]]|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/here-comes-teslas-missing-piece-battery-announcement-2015-4|access-date=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Tesla Energy also develops software to allow customers to monitor and control their systems.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Hampton |first1=Liz |last2=Jin |first2=Hyunjoo |date=September 8, 2021 |title=Tesla plans energy trading team as company expands battery projects |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/tesla-plans-begin-trading-solar-wind-battery-storage-energy-2021-09-08/ |access-date=February 3, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Delbert |first=Caroline |date=May 4, 2020 |title=Elon Musk Would Like to Help You Trade Energy |language=en-US |work=Popular Mechanics |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/science/a30153019/elon-musk-tesla-energy-autobidder/ |access-date=February 3, 2022}}</ref>

In 2022, the company deployed solar energy systems capable of generating 348 [[megawatt]]s, an increase of 3 megawatts over 2021, and deployed 6.5 gigawatt-hours of battery energy storage products, an increase of 64% over 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Scully |first=Jules |date=2023-01-26 |title=Tesla 2022 solar installs inched up to 348MW |url=https://www.pv-tech.org/tesla-2022-solar-installs-inched-up-to-348mw/ |access-date=2023-04-20 |website=PV Tech |language=en-US}}</ref>

== Other services ==
Tesla receives service revenue from its vehicle customers after their initial purchase; these revenues reached $1.47&nbsp;billion in 2022 Q2.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kolodny |first=Lora |date=July 20, 2022 |title=Tesla grows revenue 42%, but automotive margins decline |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/07/20/tesla-tsla-earnings-q2-2022-.html |access-date=August 20, 2022 |publisher=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> {{As of|2020|August}}, those services include [[#Vehicle servicing|vehicle servicing]], [[#Charging|charging]], [[#Insurance|insurance]], [[#Software upgrades|software upgrades]], and [[#Improved connectivity|improved connectivity]]. In July 2021, Tesla made Full Self-Driving available as a monthly subscription.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kolodny |first=Lora |date=July 18, 2021 |title=Tesla owners can now get 'FSD' premium driver assistance for $199 per month |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/07/17/tesla-debuts-fsd-subscription-for-199-per-month.html |access-date=August 20, 2022 |publisher=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> Future services which have been discussed include paying for a [[Hotspot (Wi-Fi)|Wi-Fi hotspot]] in the car<ref>{{cite web|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=May 23, 2017|title=Elon Musk is considering a Tesla in-car Wifi hotspot and dynamic 360-degree surround view|url=https://electrek.co/2017/05/22/tesla-wifi-hotspot-360degree-view-elon-musk/|access-date=September 20, 2020|website=Electrek|language=en-US}}</ref> and the Tesla robotaxi network.<ref>{{cite web|last=Korosec|first=Kirsten|date=April 22, 2019|title=Tesla plans to launch a robotaxi network in 2020|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2019/04/22/tesla-plans-to-launch-a-robotaxi-network-in-2020/|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US}}</ref>

[[File:Tesla_Dealership_In_Reading.jpg|thumb|Tesla dealership in [[Reading, Berkshire]]|alt=A Tesla Dealership building, cars are parked in front of the building and another car is passing by the building.]]

=== {{anchor|Charging}}Charging ===
==== {{anchor|supercharger}} Supercharger network ====
{{Main|Tesla Supercharger}}
[[File:Mall Menlo Park Mall 13.jpg|thumb|Supercharger station in [[Menlo Park, New Jersey]]<!-- Do not link Menlo Park and New Jersey separately, see MOS:GEOLINK for further guidance. -->]]

In 2012, Tesla began building a network of 480-volt fast-charging Supercharger stations. {{As of|2022|June||df=US}}, Tesla operates 36,165 Superchargers in 3,971 stations worldwide<ref>{{cite web |date=July 20, 2022 |title=Q2 2022 Update |url=https://tesla-cdn.thron.com/delivery/public/document/tesla/abc3824a-2111-4551-b957-d69b9ad97b35/S1dbei4/WEB/tsla-q2-22-update |access-date=August 3, 2022 |website=Tesla}}</ref> (an average of 9 chargers per station). The Supercharger is a proprietary [[direct current]] (DC) technology that provides up to 250&nbsp;kilowatts (kW) of power.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hoffman |first1=Connor |title=Tesla's 250-kW Supercharger Only Saved Us 2 Minutes vs. a 150-kW Charger |url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a32132062/tesla-250-kw-vs-150-kw-supercharger-tested/ |website=Car and Driver |access-date=January 26, 2021 |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> All Tesla cars except the first generation Roadster come standard with hardware to charge at Superchargers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sakelaris|first=Nicholas|date=September 16, 2013|title=Why Tesla roadster owners can't charge at new free station|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/news/2013/09/16/tesla-roadster-owners-cant-charge-at.html|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=The Business Journals}}</ref> The navigation software in Tesla cars can recommend the fastest route for long-distance travel, incorporating charging stops.<ref>{{cite web|date=March 26, 2019|title=Tesla's Navigation Eliminates The Need To Plan Charging Stops On Road Trips|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/03/26/teslas-navigation-eliminates-the-need-to-plan-charging-stops-on-road-trips/|access-date=April 8, 2020|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US}}</ref>

Model S and X cars ordered before January 15, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|last=Golson|first=Jordan|date=January 12, 2017|title=Tesla details Supercharging fees for new buyers|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/1/12/14257914/tesla-supercharger-cost-electric-car-charging|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref> and between August 3, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=August 3, 2019|title=Tesla brings back 'unsustainable' free unlimited Supercharging perk|url=https://electrek.co/2019/08/03/tesla-brings-back-unsustainable-free-unlimited-supercharging-perk/|access-date=February 23, 2020|website=Electrek|language=en-US}}</ref> and May 26, 2020,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=May 27, 2020|title=Tesla removes free Supercharging on Model S and Model X|url=https://electrek.co/2020/05/27/tesla-removes-free-supercharging-model-s-x/|access-date=June 11, 2020|website=Electrek|language=en-US}}</ref> received free unlimited supercharging. Model S and X cars ordered between January 15, 2017, and August 3, 2019, got {{cvt|400|kWh}} of free Supercharging credits per year, which provides a range of roughly {{Convert|1000|mi/yr|km/yr|lk=out|abbr=off}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Understanding Tesla's new Supercharger access for Model S and Model X |url=https://electrek.co/2017/05/20/tesla-new-supercharger-model-s-model-x/ |access-date=December 18, 2020 |work=Electrek |date=May 20, 2017}}</ref> Subsequent Tesla models never received free unlimited supercharging.<ref>{{cite web|last=Capparella|first=Joey|date=August 5, 2019|title=Tesla Brings Back Free Supercharging in Attempt to Boost Model S and Model X Sales|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a28608535/tesla-free-supercharging-model-s-x/|access-date=February 23, 2020|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US}}</ref>

==== Destination charging location network ====
[[File:TeslaDestinationCharger.jpg|thumb|upright|"Destination Charger" in North America]]

In 2014, Tesla launched the "'''Destination Charging location'''" network by providing chargers to hotels, restaurants, shopping centers and resorts (and other locations where Tesla owners may spend an hour or more) to provide on-site vehicle charging at twice the power of a typical home charging station.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lavrinc|first=Damon|date=August 28, 2014|title=Tesla Rolls Out 'Destination Charging' At Resorts And Restaurants|website=[[Jalopnik]]|location=US|url=http://jalopnik.com/tesla-rolls-out-destination-charging-at-resorts-and-res-1628225462|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>

Destination chargers are installed free of charge by Tesla-certified contractors; the locations originally were required to provide the electricity at no cost to their customers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Templeton|first=Brad|title=For Tesla Electric Car Tourism, Hotel Charging Is The Answer, Not Supercharging|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradtempleton/2019/03/28/for-tesla-electric-road-trips-hotel-charging-is-the-answer-not-supercharging/|access-date=February 23, 2020|website=Forbes|language=en}}</ref> {{As of|2022|August}}, locations with six or more destination chargers may start charging for electricity.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lambert |first=Fred |date=August 2, 2022 |title=Tesla enables paid charging at Destination Chargers, but there's a catch |url=https://electrek.co/2022/08/02/tesla-enables-paid-charging-destination-chargers-catch/ |access-date=August 4, 2022 |website=Electrek |language=en-US}}</ref> All destination chargers appear in the in-car navigation system.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla is starting to add third-party charging stations to its in-car navigation |url=https://electrek.co/2020/02/14/tesla-add-third-party-charging-stations-car-navigation/ |access-date=January 26, 2021 |work=Electrek |date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>

==== {{anchor|NACS}} North American Charging Standard ====
{{main| North American Charging Standard}}

In November 2022, Tesla renamed its previously proprietary charging connector to "[[North American Charging Standard]]" (NACS), and made the specifications available to other EV manufacturers. The name was criticized, as at the time of the announcement the connector was not the standard in North America, with all other automakers using the [[Combined Charging System]] (CCS) connector. Tesla argued that its NACS should become the connector of choice because it is more compact, its vehicles outnumber CCS equipped vehicles by a margin of two-to-one and that there were then 60% more NACS connectors installed than CCS connectors.<ref name=verge20221111>{{cite news |last=Shakir|first=Umar |date=November 11, 2022 |title=Tesla opens up its charging connector in a bid to become the North American standard |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/11/11/23453587/tesla-connector-north-american-standard-ccs-combo |access-date=November 11, 2022 |work=[[The Verge]] }}</ref><ref name=electrek20221111>{{cite news |title=Tesla opens its EV charge connector in the hope of making it the new standard |last=Lambert|first=Fred |date=November 11, 2022  |url=https://electrek.co/2022/11/11/tesla-opens-ev-charge-connector-hope-making-new-standard/ |access-date=November 11, 2022 |work=Electrek }}</ref><ref name=msn20221111>{{Cite web |title=Tesla Aims To Fix American EV Charging Infrastructure With The North American Charging Standard |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/news/tesla-aims-to-fix-american-ev-charging-infrastructure-with-the-north-american-charging-standard/ar-AA1416HJ  |date=November 11, 2022 |access-date=November 11, 2022 |work=MSN }}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |title=Opening the North American Charging Standard |url=https://www.tesla.com/blog/opening-north-american-charging-standard |date=November 11, 2022 |access-date=November 12, 2022 |publisher=Tesla |location=US}}</ref>

In May 2023, Ford announced integration of the NACS system into their electric vehicles. Starting from mid-2024, new Ford electric vehicles will have native NACS charge ports. Legacy Ford electric models will be able to connect to the NACS system and its chargers by use of an adapter.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2023/05/ford-evs-will-get-access-to-teslas-supercharger-network-in-2024/ |title=Ford EVs will get access to Tesla’s Supercharger network in 2024 |first=Jonathan M. |last=Gitlin |work=Ars Technica |location=US |date=26 May 2023 |access-date=2023-05-26}}</ref>

=== {{anchor|Software upgrades}}Software updates and upgrades ===
Tesla vehicles receive regular [[over-the-air update]]s when new software and firmware versions are released. This allows the cars to remain up to date and improve after purchase.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla's over-the-air software updates make other vehicles 'highly vulnerable to obsolescence', says analyst |url=https://electrek.co/2017/07/19/tesla-software-updates-vs-auto-industry/ |access-date=December 18, 2020 |work=Electrek |date=July 19, 2017}}</ref> Tesla also offers the option to unlock features in the car through over-the-air software upgrades after purchase. Available upgrades include basic Autopilot, Full Self Driving,<ref>{{cite web|last=Baldwin|first=Roberto|date=June 22, 2020|title=Musk Announces Tesla Basic Autopilot Deal|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a32935630/musk-tesla-autopilot-upgrade-deal-june/|access-date=August 26, 2020|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US}}</ref> acceleration boost (for Model 3 owners),<ref>{{Cite news|title=Make your Model 3 quicker with this option from Tesla|url=https://evannex.com/blogs/news/is-the-2-000-tesla-model-3-acceleration-boost-worth-it|access-date=August 26, 2020|website=evannex.com|language=en |date= January 19, 2020| first=Denis |last=Gurskiy}}</ref> and rear-heated seats (for Model 3 owners).<ref>{{cite web|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=February 15, 2020|title=Tesla starts selling rear-heated seats on Model 3 SR and SR Plus as $300 OTA upgrade|url=https://electrek.co/2020/02/15/tesla-rear-heated-seats-model-3-ota-upgrades/|access-date=September 1, 2020|website=Electrek|language=en}}</ref>

=== {{anchor|Improved connectivity}}Connectivity ===
All Tesla cars come with "Standard Connectivity" which provides navigation using a cellular connection, and the following only over [[Wi-Fi]] or [[Bluetooth]]: internet browsing, [[music streaming]] (with a paid subscription), and, when parked, video streaming and "[[caraoke]]".<ref name="electrek_connectivity_2019">{{cite news |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla starts charging $10 a month for its 'premium connectivity' features |url=https://electrek.co/2019/12/07/tesla-starts-chargin-month-premium-connectivity-features/ |access-date=January 26, 2021 |work=Electrek |date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> "Premium Connectivity" adds cellular access to those features and also provides [[Traffic reporting|live traffic]] and [[satellite map]]s for navigation.<ref name="electrek_connectivity_2019" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=September 26, 2019|title=Tesla Adds Spotify, Netflix, YouTube and Hulu Support|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/tesla-spotify-netflix-youtube-hulu-1203350885/|access-date=August 27, 2020|website=Variety|language=en}}</ref>

=== {{Anchor|Vehicle servicing}}Vehicle servicing ===
Tesla service strategy is to service its vehicles first through remote diagnosis and repair. If it is not possible to resolve a problem remotely, customers are referred to a local Tesla-owned service center, or a mobile technician is dispatched.<ref>{{cite web|date=March 21, 2019|title=Tesla Service Struggles To Keep Up With Sales Volume|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/03/21/tesla-service-struggles-to-keep-up-with-sales-volume/|access-date=September 1, 2020|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla Mobile Service|url=https://electrek.co/guides/tesla-mobile-service/|access-date=September 1, 2020|website=Electrek|language=en-US}}</ref> Tesla has said that it does not want to make a profit on vehicle servicing, which has traditionally been a large profit center for most auto dealerships.<ref name="Yarrow 2014">{{Cite news |last=Yarow |first=Jay |date=March 12, 2014 |title=Watch Elon Musk Make An Emotional Speech About How Auto Dealers Are 'Perverting Democracy' To Destroy Tesla And Hurt Customers |language=en-US |work=Business Insider |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-on-teslas-auto-dealer-model-2014-3 |access-date=July 21, 2021}}</ref>

In 2016, Tesla recommended having any Tesla car inspected every 12,500 miles or once a year, whichever comes first. In early 2019, the manual was changed to say: "your Tesla does not require annual maintenance and regular fluid changes," and instead it recommends periodic servicing of the brake fluid, air conditioning, tires and air filters.<ref name="Dent-2019">{{cite news|last=Dent|first=Steve|date=March 22, 2019|title=Tesla drops annual servicing for 'as needed' repair model|work=Engadget|location=US|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/03/22/tesla-annual-servicing-now-as-needed/|access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref>

=== {{anchor|Insurance}}Insurance ===
On June 4, 2017, the [[American Automobile Association]] raised insurance rates for Tesla owners following a report from the Highway Loss Data Institute.<ref name="Glon-2017" /> The report concluded that the Model S crashes 46% more often and is 50% more expensive to repair than comparable vehicles.<ref name="Glon-2017" /> Similarly, the Model X was concluded to crash 41% more often and to be 89% more expensive to repair than similar vehicles.<ref name="Glon-2017" /> As a result, AAA raised insurance rates on Tesla cars by 30%.<ref name="Glon-2017" /> Tesla said that the analysis is "severely flawed and not reflective of reality", however, Tesla failed to provide any contradictory numbers.<ref name="Glon-2017">{{cite web |url=http://www.leftlanenews.com/aaa-raising-insurance-costs-for-tesla-owners-96345.html |title=AAA raising insurance rates for Tesla owners |last=Glon |first=Ronan |date=June 4, 2017 |publisher=Left Lane News |access-date=June 7, 2017 |archive-date=June 6, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606123925/http://www.leftlanenews.com/aaa-raising-insurance-costs-for-tesla-owners-96345.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> Shortly thereafter, Russ Rader, the spokesman for the [[Insurance Institute for Highway Safety]], confirmed the AAA's analysis and that "Teslas get into a lot of crashes and are costly to repair afterward".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.autonews.com/article/20170604/FINANCE_AND_INSURANCE/170609884/-tesla-owners-should-pay-more-for-insurance-aaa-says |title=Tesla owners should pay more for insurance, AAA says |last=Burke |first=Katie |date=June 4, 2017 |newspaper=Automotive News |access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://jalopnik.com/aaa-raises-insurance-rates-on-tesla-vehicles-1795814904 |title=AAA Raises Insurance Rates On Tesla Vehicles Because Repairs Are So Costly |last=Felton |first=Ryan |website=[[Jalopnik]] |date=June 5, 2017|access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> The following year, an analysis of claim frequency and insurance cost data by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety conducted by financial research provider 24/7 Wall St. found that the Tesla Model S and Model X were the two most expensive vehicles to insure.<ref name="reuters1" /> Musk stated that he expects these insurance rates will greatly decrease once driver-assist and self-driving technology become commonplace.<ref name="reuters1">{{cite news|last1=Barlyn|first1=Suzanne|last2=Mathias|first2=Tamara|date=August 28, 2019|title=Tesla rolls out insurance in California|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-markel-insurance/tesla-rolls-out-insurance-in-california-idUSKCN1VI2QZ|work=Reuters|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref>

Starting in October 2017, Tesla partnered with [[Liberty Mutual Insurance Company]] to offer US customers an insurance plan designed specifically for Tesla cars.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Moffat|first=Anne Riley|date=October 13, 2017|title=Tesla Partners With Liberty Mutual for Customized Insurance Plan|language=en|work=Bloomberg.com|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-13/tesla-partners-with-liberty-mutual-for-customized-insurance-plan|access-date=March 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Muoio|first=Danielle|date=October 21, 2017|title=Tesla strikes another deal that shows it's about to turn the car insurance world upside down|work=Business Insider|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-liberty-mutual-create-customize-insurance-package-2017-10|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> In August 2019, this partnership was superseded by a partnership with State National Insurance,<ref name="Fortuna-2020">{{cite web|last=Fortuna|first=Carolyn|date=August 9, 2020|title=Tesla Insurance 101|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/08/09/tesla-insurance-101/|access-date=August 24, 2020|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=O'Brien|first=Sarah|date=September 18, 2019|title=Tesla dips into the car insurance business. Whether it would cost less is not clear|publisher=CNBC|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/18/tesla-wants-your-car-insurance-business-it-may-not-save-you-money.html|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> but was initially only available to Tesla owners in California.<ref name="Fortuna-2020" /> In July 2020, Musk, relying on data obtained through the partnership with State National Insurance, announced that Tesla was creating its own "major" insurance company.<ref name="Sully-2020">{{cite news|last=Sully|first=Evan|date=October 21, 2020|title=Experts say Tesla's unique data-tracking abilities give it an advantage as Elon Musk looks to build a 'major insurance company' for Tesla owners|work=Business Insider|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-vehicle-data-advantage-car-insurance-ambitions-elon-musk-analysts-2020-10|access-date=November 29, 2020}}</ref> Tesla claims the insurance uses individual vehicle data to offer personalized pricing.<ref name="Sully-2020" />

{{As of|2023|January}}, Tesla offers insurance in Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Maryland, Minnesota, Nevada, Ohio, Oregon, Texas, Utah and Virginia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla expands its own insurance based on real-time driver data to two more states – now in 10 states|url=https://electrek.co/2022/07/26/tesla-expands-insurance-based-on-real-time-driver-data-two-more-states/|access-date=January 2, 2022 |website=electrek.co|language=en-US}}</ref>

== Business strategy ==
[[File:Tesla auto bots.jpg|thumb|[[industrial robot|Robotic]] manufacturing of the Model S at the [[Tesla Factory]] in [[Fremont, California]]]]

At the time of Tesla's founding in 2003, electric vehicles were very expensive.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Kevin A.|date=March 15, 2018|title=Worth the Watt: A Brief History of the Electric Car, 1830 to Present|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/features/g15378765/worth-the-watt-a-brief-history-of-the-electric-car-1830-to-present|access-date=July 10, 2021|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2006, Elon Musk stated that Tesla's strategy was to first produce high-price, low-volume vehicles, such as sports cars, for which customers are less sensitive to price. This would allow them to progressively bring down the cost of batteries, which in turn would allow them to offer cheaper and higher volume cars.<ref name="MasterPlan" /><ref name="bbweek20070730">{{Cite news |last=Welch |first=David |date=July 30, 2007 |title=Tesla: A Carmaker With Silicon Valley Spark |publisher=BloombergBusinessweek |url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2007-07-29/tesla-a-carmaker-with-silicon-valley-spark |url-status=dead |access-date=March 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914195549/http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2007-07-29/tesla-a-carmaker-with-silicon-valley-spark |archive-date=September 14, 2014}}</ref> Tesla's first vehicle, the Roadster, was low-volume (fewer than 2,500 were produced) and priced at over $100,000. The next models, the Model S and Model X, are more affordable but still luxury vehicles. The most recent models, the Model 3 and the Model Y, are priced still lower, and aimed at a higher volume market,<ref name=20K>{{Cite news |title=Elon Musk Envisions Tesla Electric Car as Low as $20K |url=https://gigaom.com/2008/09/17/elon-musk-envisions-tesla-electric-car-as-low-as-20k/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312185643/https://gigaom.com/2008/09/17/elon-musk-envisions-tesla-electric-car-as-low-as-20k/ |archive-date=March 12, 2015 | work=[[GigaOm]] | date=September 17, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Vaughan |first=Adam  |title=12 interesting things we learned from Tesla's Elon Musk this week |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/oct/25/things-learned-tesla-elon-musk-electric-car |date=October 25, 2013}}</ref> selling over 100,000 vehicles each quarter. Tesla continuously updates the hardware of its cars rather than waiting for a new model year, as opposed to nearly every other car manufacturer.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Tesla Introduced A Business Model The World Has Not Seen Before |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/08/29/tesla-introduced-a-business-model-the-world-has-not-seen-before/ |website=[[CleanTechnica]] |date=August 29, 2020}}</ref>

Unlike other automakers, Tesla does not rely on franchised [[auto dealership]]s to sell vehicles. Instead, the company directly sells vehicles through its website and a network of company-owned stores.<ref>{{cite web|last=Read|first=Richard|title=GM Follows Tesla's Lead, Plans To Sell Directly To Online Shoppers|url=https://www.thecarconnection.com/news/1087492_gm-follows-teslas-lead-plans-to-sell-directly-to-online-shoppers|access-date=February 2, 2020|website=The Car Connection|language=en}}</ref><ref name="7Reasons">{{cite web|date=January 19, 2016|title=7 Reasons Why Tesla Insists on Selling its Own Cars|url=https://fortune.com/2016/01/19/why-tesla-sells-directly/|website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref> The company is the first automaker in the United States to sell cars directly to consumers.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Toole|first=James|date=July 2, 2013|title=Tesla direct-sales petition hits 100,000 signatures|publisher=[[CNN]]|url=https://money.cnn.com/2013/07/02/autos/tesla-petition/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Shipley|first=Lou|date=February 28, 2020|title=How Tesla Sets Itself Apart|work=[[Harvard Business Review]]|url=https://hbr.org/2020/02/how-tesla-sets-itself-apart|issn=0017-8012}}</ref> Some jurisdictions, particularly in the United States, prohibit auto manufacturers from directly selling vehicles to consumers. In these areas, Tesla has locations that it calls ''galleries'' that the company says "educate and inform customers about our products, but such locations do not actually transact in the sale of vehicles."<ref name="10K_2021">{{cite web |title=Annual report Form 10-K 2021 Tesla Inc. |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1318605/000095017022000796/tsla-20211231.htm| publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-06-20/news/ct-oped-0620-chapman-20130620_1_tesla-motors-car-dealers-car-costs |work=Chicago Tribune |first=Steve |last=Chapman |title=Car buyers get hijacked |date=June 20, 2013 |access-date=April 12, 2015}}</ref> In total, Tesla operates nearly 400 stores and galleries in more than 35 countries.<ref>{{cite web|date=April 2, 2021| title=Tesla Stores |url=https://www.tesla.com/en_EU/findus/list|website=Tesla}}</ref> These locations are typically located in retail shopping districts, inside shopping malls, or other high-traffic areas,<ref name="7Reasons" /> instead of near other auto dealerships.<ref name=bypass>{{Cite news |last=Borchers |first=Callum |date=November 20, 2013 |title=Automaker Tesla looks to bypass car dealers |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/11/20/tesla-battles-auto-dealers-direct-sales-consumers/3f1xBFN21xH8QqQc3jijTP/story.html | url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://insideevs.com/features/394452/tesla-transforming-car-dealership/ | title=Tesla Has Altered The Car Dealership Model for the Better | work=[[InsideEVs]] | date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/2013/05/20/autos/telsa-car-dealers/ | title=Tesla's fight with America's car dealers | first=Peter |last=Valdes-Dapena | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=May 20, 2013}}</ref>

Tesla is notable for spending no money on paid advertising campaigns, unlike other automakers.<ref>{{cite web|date=December 13, 2021|title=Tesla's great year came without paid advertising, but plenty of buzz|url=https://adage.com/article/special-report-marketers-year/ad-age-2021-best-marketers-tesla/2384076|access-date=January 30, 2022|website=Advertising Age|language=en}}</ref>

[[File:The Tesla Patent Wall at HQ, now set free.jpg|thumb|The Tesla Patent Wall at its headquarters was removed after the company announced its [[patents]] are part of the [[Open-source-software movement|open source movement]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/tesla-motors-opens-patents-elon-musks-electric-cars-now-part-open-source-movement-1600522 |title=Tesla Motors Opens Patents: Elon Musk's Electric Cars Now Part Of 'Open Source Movement' |first=Maria |last=Gallucci |date=June 13, 2014 |newspaper=HybridCars.com |access-date=June 14, 2014}}</ref>]]

Tesla has a high degree of [[vertical integration]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jin|first=Hyunjoo|date=January 4, 2022|title=Explainer: How Tesla weathered global supply chain issues that knocked rivals|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/markets/europe/how-tesla-weathered-global-supply-chain-issues-that-knocked-rivals-2022-01-04/|access-date=January 30, 2022}}</ref> estimated at 80% in 2016.<ref name="gs2016-02-26">{{cite news|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=February 26, 2016|title=Tesla is now ~80% vertically integrated, says Goldman Sachs after a Tesla Factory visit|website=[[electrek.co]]|url=http://electrek.co/2016/02/26/tesla-vertically-integrated/|access-date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> The company produces vehicle components as well as building proprietary stations where customers can charge their vehicles. Vertical integration is rare in the automotive industry, where companies typically ''outsource'' 80% of components to suppliers and focus on engine manufacturing and final assembly.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McAssey|first1=Pat|date=October 13, 2016|title=Volkswagen CEO 'Annoyed Beyond Measure' That DHL Made Electric Van|url=http://nesnfuel.com/2016/10/13/volkswagen-ceo-annoyed-beyond-measure-that-dhl-made-electric-van/|access-date=October 20, 2016|work=NESN Fuel|archive-date=August 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809020608/https://nesn.com/nesn-fuel/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alternative Fuels Data Center: Developing Infrastructure to Charge Plug-In Electric Vehicles|url=http://www.afdc.energy.gov/fuels/electricity_infrastructure.html|access-date=April 10, 2016|website=afdc.energy.gov|publisher=[[United States Department of Energy]]}}</ref> Tesla used low-cost strategy as a business approach, with which they can expand their business into a broader market by offering standard technology items.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Stringham |first1=Edward Peter |last2=Miller |first2=Jennifer Kelly |last3=Clark |first3=J.R. |title=Overcoming Barriers to Entry in an Established Industry: Tesla Motors |url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1525/cmr.2015.57.4.85 |journal=California Management Review |year=2015 |language=en |volume=57 |issue=4 |pages=85–103 |doi=10.1525/cmr.2015.57.4.85 |s2cid=155655599 |issn=0008-1256}}</ref>

Tesla generally allows its competitors to license its technology, stating that it wants to help its competitors accelerate the world's use of sustainable energy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Korzeniewski|first=Jeremy|date=July 29, 2020|title=Elon Musk: Tesla would share batteries, technology with competitors|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2020/07/29/tesla-supplying-batteries-tech-competitors/|access-date=October 11, 2020|website=Autoblog|language=en}}</ref> Licensing agreements include provisions whereby the recipient agrees not to file patent suits against Tesla, or to copy its designs directly.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/06/14/heres-what-teslas-good-faith-patent-stance-actually-means/ |title=Here's what Tesla's 'good faith' patent stance actually means |first=Eric |last=Blattberg |date=June 14, 2014 |work=VentureBeat |access-date=April 12, 2015}}</ref> Tesla retains control of its other intellectual property, such as trademarks and [[trade secret]]s to prevent direct copying of its technology.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gigaom.com/2014/06/14/what-elon-musk-did-and-did-not-do-when-he-opened-teslas-patents/ |title=What Elon Musk did – and did not – do when he "opened" Tesla's patents |first=Jeff John |last=Roberts |date=June 14, 2014 |publisher=GigaOm |access-date=April 12, 2015 |archive-date=January 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119172026/https://gigaom.com/2014/06/14/what-elon-musk-did-and-did-not-do-when-he-opened-teslas-patents/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

== Technology ==
Tesla develops many components in-house, such as batteries, motors, and software.<ref name="gs2016-02-26" />

=== Vehicle batteries ===
[[File:Tesla chassis, Sydney - Martin Place, 2017 (01).jpg|thumb|Tesla vehicle [[chassis]] used in [[Model S]] and [[Tesla Model X|X]], with the battery visible]]

Tesla was the first automaker to use batteries containing thousands of small, cylindrical, lithium-ion [[commodity cell]]s like those used in consumer electronics.<ref name="LeBeau-2020">{{cite web|last=LeBeau|first=Phil|date=February 10, 2020|title=Tesla's competitors play catch-up on electric batteries|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/10/teslas-competitors-play-catch-up-on-electric-batteries.html|access-date=October 11, 2020|publisher=CNBC|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=April 17, 2020|title=Demand for cylindrical battery cells for electric vehicles on rise|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/tech/2021/01/515_287209.html|access-date=January 2, 2021|website=The Korea Times|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=LFP & prismatic battery cells at core of Tesla's China strategy|date=February 19, 2020 |url=https://www.benchmarkminerals.com/membership/lfp-prismatic-cells-at-core-of-teslas-china-strategy/|access-date=January 2, 2021|publisher=[[Benchmark Mineral Intelligence]]|language=en-GB}}</ref> Tesla uses a version of these cells that is designed to be cheaper to manufacture and lighter than standard cells by removing some safety features; according to Tesla, these features are redundant because of the advanced thermal management system and an [[intumescent]] chemical in the battery to prevent fires.<ref name="gcr2013-06">{{cite news |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1084682_what-goes-into-a-tesla-model-s-battery--and-what-it-may-cost |title=What Goes into A Tesla Model S Battery – And What It May Cost |first=Thomas |last=Fisher |website=Green Car Reports |date=June 11, 2013 |access-date=February 11, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190503210702/https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1084682_what-goes-into-a-tesla-model-s-battery--and-what-it-may-cost |archive-date=May 3, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The batteries are placed under the vehicle floor. This saves interior and trunk (boot) space but increases the risk of battery damage by debris or impact (see [[#Fires|crashes and fires]]). After two vehicle fires in 2013 due to [[road debris]], the Model S was retrofitted with a multi-part aluminum and titanium protection system to reduce the possibility of damage.<ref name="model-s-titanium">{{cite web|last=Prince|first=Max|date=March 28, 2014|title=Meet the up-armored, titanium-shielded Tesla Model S|url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/go/news/tesla-model-s-titanium-underbody-shield|access-date=October 6, 2020|website=Road & Track|language=en-US}}</ref>

In 2016, former Tesla CTO J.B. Straubel expected batteries to last 10–15 years,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2016/09/06/tesla-cto-tesla-batteries-expected-last-10-15-years-minimum/ |title=Tesla CTO: Tesla Batteries Expected To Last 10–15 Years At A Minimum |website=CleanTechnica |date=September 6, 2016 |access-date=September 7, 2016}}</ref> and discounted using electric cars to charge the grid with [[vehicle-to-grid]] because the related battery wear outweighs economic benefit.<ref name="CleanTechnica-2016" /> He also preferred recycling over [[Battery storage|re-use for grid]] once they reach the end of their useful life for vehicles.<ref name="CleanTechnica-2016">{{cite web |url=http://cleantechnica.com/2016/08/22/vehicle-to-grid-used-ev-batteries-grid-storage/ |title=Why Vehicle-To-Grid & Used EV Battery Storage Isn't Logical |website=CleanTechnica |date=August 22, 2016 |access-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.luxresearchinc.com/news-and-events/press-releases/read/recycling-not-reuse-better-choice-batteries-retired-electric |title=Recycling, not Reuse, Is the Better Choice for Batteries from Retired Electric Vehicles |first=Carole |last=Jacques |publisher=Lux Research |date=November 22, 2016 |access-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref> Tesla launched its battery recycling operation at [[Giga Nevada]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|date=April 16, 2019|title=Tesla launches battery recycling at Nevada Gigafactory|url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1122631_tesla-launches-battery-recycling-at-nevada-gigafactory|access-date=September 19, 2020|website=Green Car Reports|language=en}}</ref> Straubel independently founded battery recycling company [[Redwood Materials, Inc.|Redwood Materials]] in 2017, which supplies recycled materials to Panasonic.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Korosec |first=Kirsten |date=January 4, 2022 |title=Panasonic to use Redwood's recycled materials in battery cell production at Tesla gigafactory |url=https://techcrunch.com/2022/01/04/panasonic-redwood-battery-cell-production-tesla/ |access-date=November 12, 2022 |website=TechCrunch |language=en-US}}</ref>

[[Panasonic]] is Tesla's supplier of cells in the United States, and cooperates with Tesla in producing cylindrical [[2170 battery|2170 batteries]] at Giga Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Panasonic to expand battery capacity at Tesla Gigafactory|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2020/09/08/panasonic-to-expand-battery-capacity-at-tesla-gigafactory/|access-date=April 7, 2021|website=TechCrunch|date=September 8, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref>
In January 2021, Panasonic had the capacity to produce 39 GWh per year of batteries at Giga Nevada.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gurskiy |first1=Denis |title=Tesla Factory: Stats, Production, History, and Delivery Numbers by Gigafactory |url=https://evbite.com/tesla-factory-stats-production-history-and-delivery-numbers-by-gigafactory/ |access-date=February 1, 2021 |work=EVBite |date=January 27, 2021}}</ref> Tesla's battery cells used in Giga Shanghai are supplied by Panasonic and [[Contemporary Amperex Technology]] (CATL), and are the more traditional [[Prism (geometry)|prismatic]] (rectangular) cells used by other automakers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sanderson|first=Henry|date=February 19, 2020|title=Tesla's choice of cheaper lithium batteries hits cobalt miners|url=https://www.ft.com/content/7264bdda-5310-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20221211231233/https://www.ft.com/content/7264bdda-5310-11ea-90ad-25e377c0ee1f|archive-date=December 11, 2022|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|website=Financial Times|access-date=May 6, 2020}}</ref>
{{As of| April 2022}}, nearly half of all Tesla's vehicles produced last quarter are using cobalt-free [[Lithium iron phosphate battery]] (LFP) made in China.<ref>{{cite web|date=April 22, 2022 |first=Fred |last=Lambert |title=Tesla is already using cobalt-free LFP batteries in half of its new cars produced| url=https://electrek.co/2022/04/22/tesla-using-cobalt-free-lfp-batteries-in-half-new-cars-produced/ |website=[[Electrek]] |access-date=November 12, 2022 }}</ref>

==== Battery research ====
Tesla invests in [[lithium-ion battery]] research. Starting in 2016, the company established a 5-year battery research and development partnership at [[Dalhousie University]] in Nova Scotia, Canada, with lead researcher [[Jeff Dahn]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.dal.ca/news/2021/01/19/advanced-battery-scientists-join-exclusive-tesla-partnership-at-.html | title=Advanced Battery Scientists Join Excludive Tesla Partnership at DAL in Research Chair Roles  | first=Caitlyn | last=MacQueen | work=[[Dalhousie University]] | date=January 19, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release | url=https://www.dal.ca/news/media/media-releases/2015/06/17/tesla_motors_sign_first_canadian_university_research_agreement_with_dalhousie_university.html | title=Tesla Motors signs first Canadian university research agreement with Dalhousie University | publisher=[[Dalhousie University]] | date=June 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-autos-tesla-batteries-laboratory/how-tesla-tapped-a-tiny-canadian-lab-for-battery-breakthroughs-idUSKBN22Q1WK | title=How Tesla tapped a tiny Canadian lab for battery breakthroughs | first1=Norihiko | last1=Shirouzu | first2=Paul | last2=Lienert | work=[[Reuters]] | date=May 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://electrek.co/2020/01/09/tesla-jeff-dahn-new-head-advanced-battery-research-canada/ |title=Tesla is going to have new head of its Advanced Battery Research in Canada |last=Lambert |first=Fred |website=[[Electrek]] |date=January 9, 2020}}</ref> Tesla acquired two battery companies: Maxwell Technologies, acquired for over $200 million<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://electrek.co/2020/01/21/tesla-acquisition-maxwell-big-impact-battery-elon-musk/ | title=Elon Musk: Tesla acquisition of Maxwell is going to have a very big impact on batteries | first=Fred | last=Lambert | work=[[Electrek]] | date=January 21, 2020}}</ref> – but sold in 2021<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://electrek.co/2021/07/21/tesla-tsla-sells-back-maxwell-technology-ultracapacitor-business-to-former-executives/ | title=Tesla (TSLA) sells back Maxwell Technology's ultracapacitor business to former executives | first=Fred | last=Lambert | work=[[Electrek]] | date=July 21, 2021}}</ref> and Hibar Systems.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/10/06/tesla-adds-hibar-systems-to-its-list-of-acquisitions/ |title=Tesla Adds Hibar Systems To Its List Of Acquisitions | website=[[CleanTechnica]] |date=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/07/tesla-reportedly-bought-a-company-for-high-speed-battery-manufacturing.html |title=Tesla reportedly bought a company that specializes in high-speed battery manufacturing |last=Palmer |first=Annie |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>

During Tesla's Battery Day event on September 22, 2020, Tesla announced the next generation of batteries, featuring a tab-less battery design to increase the range and decrease the price of Tesla vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hawkins | first=Andrew J. |title=Tesla announces "tabless" battery cells that will improve range of its electric cars | url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/9/22/21449238/tesla-electric-car-battery-tabless-cells-day-elon-musk |work=[[The Verge]] |date=September 22, 2020}}</ref> The new battery is named the "4680" in reference to its dimensions: {{Convert|46|mm|in|abbr=out}} wide by {{Convert|80|mm|in|abbr=out}} tall.<ref>{{Cite news| date=September 24, 2020 | first=Charles | last= Morris| title=Charged EVs {{!}} Tesla Battery Day: a raft of tech advances will deliver cost reductions worth waiting for|url=https://chargedevs.com/newswire/tesla-battery-day-a-raft-of-tech-advances-will-deliver-cost-reductions-worth-waiting-for/|access-date=October 8, 2020| website=chargedevs.com|publisher=Charged }}</ref> Two weeks before Battery Day, Tesla paid a total of $3 to buy several battery manufacturing patent applications from Springpower International, a small Canadian battery company.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Tesla taps tiny startup's tech to build cheaper, cleaner batteries | url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/05/04/tesla-taps-tiny-startups-tech-to-build-cheaper-cleaner-batteries/ | website=[[TechCrunch]]| date=May 4, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.engadget.com/tesla-springpower-international-patents-190100400.html | title=Tesla may have paid $3 to buy patents for making cleaner EV batteries | first=Igor | last=Bonifacic | work=[[Engadget]] | date=May 4, 2021}}</ref>

Tesla predicted the new batteries could be up to 56% cheaper and allow the cars to have a 54% longer range.<ref>{{cite web |last=Templeton |first=Brad |title=Tesla 'Battery Day' Promises 56% Reduction in Battery Cost And Much More |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bradtempleton/2020/09/22/tesla-battery-day-promises-56-reduction-in-battery-cost-and-much-more/ |website=[[Forbes]]| date=September 22, 2020}}</ref> The company said this would be achieved by a more efficient production process, new battery design, cheaper resources for the anode and cathode, and better integration into the vehicle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla seeking 56% cut in $/kWh, $25K EV in three years through manufacturing and design innovations |url=https://www.greencarcongress.com/2020/09/20200923-tesla.html|access-date=October 3, 2020|website=Green Car Congress}}</ref> Business analysis company [[BloombergNEF]] estimated Tesla's battery pack price in 2021 at $112 per kWh, versus an industry average of $132 per kWh.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Timothy|date=December 13, 2021|title=Why battery costs have plunged 89 percent since 2010|url=https://fullstackeconomics.com/untitled-2/|access-date=January 30, 2022|website=Full Stack Economics|language=en|quote=Tesla hasn't shared its exact battery costs with BloombergNEF, but the group estimates Tesla spends $112 per kWh – 15 percent below the industry average of $132.}}</ref> {{As of|2021|December}}, BloombergNEF estimates the industry as a whole will reach $100 per kWh in 2024.<ref>{{cite web|last=Colthorpe|first=Andy|date=December 1, 2021|title=BloombergNEF: Average battery pack prices to drop below US$100/kWh by 2024 despite near-term spikes|url=https://www.energy-storage.news/bloombergnef-average-battery-pack-prices-to-drop-below-us100-kwh-by-2024-despite-near-term-spikes/|access-date=January 30, 2022|website=Energy Storage News|language=en-US}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Energy]] estimated in 2020 that battery prices of about $100 per kWh would cause electric cars to reach cost parity with their gasoline-powered counterparts, which in turn would accelerate sales of new electric cars.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rathi |first=Akshat|title=The Magic Number That Unlocks The Electric-Car Revolution |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-09-22/elon-musk-s-battery-day-could-reveal-very-cheap-batteries |date=September 22, 2020 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P. | url-access=subscription}}</ref>

=== Motors ===
Tesla makes two kinds of electric motors. Its oldest design in production is a [[Three-phase electric power|three-phase]] four-pole alternating current [[induction motor]] with a copper [[Rotor (electric)|rotor]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla's 3-Phase 4-Pole AC Induction Motor – Why Nikola Tesla's 19th Century Induction Motor Is The Ideal Choice for the 21st Century Electric Car |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2016/05/30/nikola-teslas-19th-century-induction-motor-ideal-choice-21st-century-electric-car/ |access-date=January 26, 2021 |work=CleanTechnica |date=May 30, 2016}}</ref> (which inspired the Tesla logo), which is used as the rear motor in the Model S and Model X. Newer, higher-efficiency [[permanent magnet motor]]s are used in the Model 3, Model Y, the front motor of 2019-onward versions of the Model S and X, and are expected to be used in the Tesla Semi.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2019/04/motor-technology-from-model-3-helps-tesla-boost-model-s-range-10/ |title=Motor technology from Model 3 helps Tesla boost Model S range 10% |website=[[ArsTechnica]] |date=April 24, 2019}}</ref> The permanent magnet motors increase efficiency, especially in stop-start driving.<ref>{{cite web|last=Huynh |first=TA |title=Performance Analysis of Permanent Magnet Motors for Electric Vehicles Traction Considering Driving Cycles |url=https://www.mdpi.com/1996-1073/11/6/1385/pdf}}</ref>

=== {{anchor|AutoPilot}}Autopilot ===
{{Main|Tesla Autopilot}}
[[File:Tesla Autopilot Engaged in Model X.jpg|thumb|Tesla Autopilot in operation]]

Autopilot is an [[advanced driver-assistance system]] developed by Tesla. The system requires active driver supervision at all times.<ref>{{cite web| title=Apple engineer killed in Tesla SUV crash on Silicon Valley freeway was playing videogame: NTSB| url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/apple-engineer-killed-in-tesla-suv-crash-on-silicon-valley-freeway-was-playing-videogame-ntsb-2020-02-25 | website=[[MarketWatch]] |date=February 25, 2020 | url-access=limited}}</ref>

Since September 2014, all Tesla cars are shipped with sensors (initially hardware version 1 or "HW1") and software to support Autopilot.<ref name="electrek.co">{{cite web |last=Lambert| first=Fred|title=Understanding Tesla's self-driving features: The Autopilot|url=https://electrek.co/2015/06/16/understanding-teslas-self-driving-features-the-autopilot/ |website=[[Electrek]] |date=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Tesla upgraded its sensors and software in October 2016 ("HW2") to support full self-driving in the future.<ref name=8cameras>{{Cite news |last=Lambert |first=Fred|title=A look at Tesla's new Autopilot hardware suite: 8 cameras, 1 radar, ultrasonics & new supercomputer |url=https://electrek.co/2016/10/20/tesla-new-autopilot-hardware-suite-camera-nvidia-tesla-vision/ |website=[[Electrek]] |date=October 20, 2016}}</ref> HW2 includes eight cameras, twelve [[ultrasonic sensor]]s, and forward-facing [[radar]].<ref name=8cameras /> HW2.5 was released in mid-2017, and it upgraded HW2 with a second [[graphics processing unit]] (GPU) and, for the Model 3 only, a driver-facing camera.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://electrek.co/2017/08/09/tesla-autopilot-2-5-hardware-computer-autonomous-driving/ |title=Tesla has a new Autopilot '2.5' hardware suite with more computing power for autonomous driving |last=Lambert |first=Fred |work=[[Electrek]] |date=August 9, 2017}}</ref> HW3 was released in early 2019 with an updated and more powerful computer, employing a custom Tesla-designed [[system on a chip]].<ref name="electrek_hw3_2019">{{Cite news |url=https://electrek.co/2019/01/04/tesla-leaks-hardware-3-self-driving-computer/ |title=Tesla leaks info about new self-driving computer in latest software update |last=Lambert |first=Fred |website=[[Electrek]] |date=January 4, 2019}}</ref>

In April 2019, Tesla announced that all of its cars will include Autopilot software (defined as just ''Traffic-Aware Cruise Control'' and ''Autosteer'' (Beta)) as a standard feature moving forward.<ref name=BusinessInsider_201904>{{cite news |last1=Logan |first1=Bryan |title=Tesla made Autopilot a standard feature on all its vehicles and announced sweeping changes to the Model 3 lineup |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-model-3-lineup-changes-autopilot-comes-standard-2019-4 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref> Full self-driving software ([[Automatic parking|Autopark]], Navigate on Autopilot (Beta), Auto Lane Change (Beta), [[Tesla Autopilot#Summon (Beta)|Summon (Beta)]], [[Tesla Autopilot#Smart Summon (Beta)|Smart Summon (Beta)]] and future abilities) is an extra cost option.<ref name=BusinessInsider_201904 />

In 2020, Tesla released software updates where its cars recognize and automatically stop at stop signs and traffic lights.<ref>{{cite web|title=Teslas can now see and slow for traffic lights and stop signs |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/27/21238637/tesla-cars-traffic-light-stop-sign-control-feature-self-driving |last=O'Kane |first=Sean |website=[[The Verge]] |date=April 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Popa |first=Bogdan |title=Tesla Cars No Longer Need Driver Input to Automatically Go Through Intersections |url=https://www.autoevolution.com/news/tesla-cars-no-longer-need-driver-input-to-automatically-go-through-intersections-149566.html |website=[[Autoevolution]] |date=October 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://electrek.co/2019/03/05/tesla-autopilot-detects-stop-lines-intersections/ | title=Tesla Autopilot now detects stop lines in move to handle intersections | first=Fred | last=Lambert | work=[[Electrek]] | date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> In May 2021, Tesla removed the radar sensor and radar features from its Model 3 and Model Y vehicles, opting instead to rely on camera vision alone.<ref>{{cite web|date=May 25, 2021|title=Transitioning to Tesla Vision|url=https://www.tesla.com/support/transitioning-tesla-vision|access-date=June 26, 2021 |website=tesla.com|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| first=Matt | last=McFarland| title=Tesla is following in the steps of an unlikely rival: Subaru|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/18/cars/tesla-radar-autopilot/index.html| publisher=[[CNN]]| date=June 18, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kolodny |first=Lora |title=Tesla is ditching radar, will rely on cameras for Autopilot in some cars |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/05/25/tesla-ditching-radar-for-autopilot-in-model-3-model-y.html |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=May 25, 2021}}</ref> The ''New York Times'' reported in December 2021 that Musk "repeatedly told members of the Autopilot team that humans could drive with only two eyes and that this meant cars should be able to drive with cameras alone," an analogy some experts and former Tesla engineers described as "deeply flawed."<ref>{{cite news|first1=Cade|last1=Metz|first2=Neal E.|last2=Boudette|access-date=December 7, 2021|title=Inside Tesla as Elon Musk Pushed an Unflinching Vision for Self-Driving Cars|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/06/technology/tesla-autopilot-elon-musk.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/06/technology/tesla-autopilot-elon-musk.html |archive-date=December 28, 2021 |url-access=limited|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 6, 2021|issn=0362-4331}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Similarly, a statistical analysis conducted in ''A Methodology for Normalizing Safety Statistics of Partially Automated Vehicles'' debunked a common Tesla claim that Autopilot reduced crash rates by 40 percent<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=February 13, 2019|title=In 2017, the feds said Tesla Autopilot cut crashes 40% – that was bogus|url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2019/02/in-2017-the-feds-said-tesla-autopilot-cut-crashes-40-that-was-bogus/|access-date=February 5, 2022|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us}}</ref> by accounting for the relative safety of the given operating domain when using active safety measures.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Goodall |first=Noah J. |date=October 26, 2021 |title=A Methodology for Normalizing Safety Statistics of Partially Automated Vehicles |publisher=Virginia Transportation Research Council |doi=10.31224/osf.io/m8j6g |s2cid=240033225 |url=https://engrxiv.org/preprint/view/1973 |language=en}}</ref>

=== Full Self-Driving ===
{{Main|Tesla Autopilot#Full Self-Driving}}

''Full Self-Driving'' (FSD) is an optional extension of Autopilot promoted as eventually being able to perform fully [[autonomous driving]]. At the end of 2016, Tesla expected to demonstrate full autonomy by the end of 2017,<ref>{{cite news | last1=Golson |first1=Jordan |last2=Bohn |first2=Dieter |date=October 19, 2016 |title=All new Tesla cars now have hardware for 'full self-driving capabilities'|website=The Verge|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/19/13340938/tesla-autopilot-update-model-3-elon-musk-update|access-date=October 22, 2016}}</ref> which {{As of|2022|July|lc=y}} has not occurred.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tesla Offers 'Full Self-Driving' Feature as a Monthly Subscription|url=https://www.consumerreports.org/autonomous-driving/tesla-full-self-driving-feature-monthly-subscription-a7568042991/|access-date=August 16, 2021|website=Consumer Reports|language=en-US}}</ref> The first beta version of the software was released on October 22, 2020, to a small group of testers.<ref name="Stoklosa-2020">{{cite web|last=Stoklosa|first=Alexander|date=October 22, 2020|title=Tesla Puts "Beta" Version of Full Self-Driving Capability in Hands of Select Few|url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-full-self-driving-beta-capability-testing/|access-date=October 25, 2020|website=Motor Trend}}</ref> The release of the beta has renewed concern regarding whether the technology is ready for testing on public roads.<ref>{{cite web|last=Holderith|first=Peter|title=Tesla's 'Full Self Driving' Beta Tech Nearly Wrecked This Model 3 Into a Parked Car|url=https://www.thedrive.com/tech/37297/teslas-full-self-driving-beta-tech-nearly-wrecked-this-model-3-into-a-parked-car|access-date=October 30, 2020|website=The Drive|date=October 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Synced|date=October 28, 2020|title=Tesla Rolls Out 'Full Self-Driving' Beta; Critics Apply the Brakes|url=https://syncedreview.com/2020/10/28/tesla-rolls-out-full-self-driving-beta-critics-apply-the-brakes/|access-date=October 30, 2020|website=Synced|language=en-US}}</ref> The [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) has called for "tougher requirements" for any testing of Autopilot on public roads.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kolodny|first=Lora|date=March 12, 2021|title=A federal agency warns Tesla tests unfinished driverless tech on its users|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/03/12/tesla-is-using-customers-to-test-av-tech-on-public-roads-ntsb.html|access-date=March 13, 2021|publisher=CNBC|language=en}}</ref>

Tesla's approach to achieve full autonomy is different from that of other companies.<ref name="Shahan-2019">{{cite web|date=June 20, 2019|title=If GM/Cruise Is Way Behind Waymo, How Does It Compare To Tesla?|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/06/20/if-gm-cruise-is-way-behind-waymo-how-does-it-compare-to-tesla/|access-date=October 23, 2020|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US}}</ref> Whereas [[Waymo]], [[Cruise (autonomous vehicle)|Cruise]], and other companies are relying on highly detailed (centimeter-scale) three-dimensional maps, [[lidar]], and cameras, as well as [[radar]] and ultrasonic sensors in their autonomous vehicles, Tesla's approach is to use coarse-grained two-dimensional maps and cameras (no lidar) as well as radar and ultrasonic sensors.<ref name="Shahan-2019" /><ref>{{cite web|date=October 12, 2020|title=Tesla Autopilot Updates & Notes from Elon Musk|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2020/10/12/tesla-autopilot-updates-notes-from-elon-musk/|access-date=October 25, 2020|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US}}</ref> Tesla claims that although its approach is much more difficult, it will ultimately be more useful, because its vehicles will be able to self-drive without geofencing concerns.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=August 6, 2019|title=Elon Musk: "Anyone relying on lidar is doomed." Experts: Maybe not|url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2019/08/elon-musk-says-driverless-cars-dont-need-lidar-experts-arent-so-sure/|access-date=April 7, 2021|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us}}</ref> Tesla's self-driving software has been trained on over 20&nbsp;billion miles driven by Tesla vehicles as of January 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Klender |first1=Joey |title=Tesla dials in on FSD improvements with 'millimeter-wave radar sensor' filing |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-millimeter-wave-radar-sensor/ |access-date=February 1, 2021 |work=Teslarati |date=January 14, 2021}}</ref> Tesla also designed a self-driving computer chip that has been installed in its cars since March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Agarwal|first=Yash|date=September 3, 2019|title=Tesla develops new chip : has it finally cracked full autonomous driving?|url=https://drivetribe.com/p/tesla-develops-new-chip-has-it-Ua64gIycTYyUuiAyTPIRmQ|access-date=October 24, 2020|website=DriveTribe|language=en|archive-date=November 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201125225116/https://drivetribe.com/p/tesla-develops-new-chip-has-it-Ua64gIycTYyUuiAyTPIRmQ|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Most experts believe that Tesla's approach of trying to achieve full self-driving by eschewing lidar and high-definition maps is not feasible.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hawkins|first=Andrew J.|date=April 24, 2019|title=It's Elon Musk vs. everyone else in the race for fully driverless cars|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/24/18512580/elon-musk-tesla-driverless-cars-lidar-simulation-waymo|access-date=April 29, 2020|website=The Verge|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=July 20, 2020|title=Tesla's plan for Level 5 not feasible, experts say|url=https://www.autonews.com/mobility-report/teslas-plan-level-5-not-feasible-experts-say|access-date=October 30, 2020|website=Automotive News|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Group |first=SAE Media |title=Is Lidar Necessary for Autonomous Vehicles? |url=https://www.techbriefs.com/component/content/article/tb/stories/blog/45654 |access-date=October 19, 2022 |website=techbriefs.com |language=en}}</ref> In March 2021, according to a letter that Tesla sent to the [[California Department of Motor Vehicles]] about FSD's capability – acquired by [[PlainSite]] via a public records request – Tesla stated that FSD is not capable of autonomous driving and is only at [[Society of Automotive Engineers]] Level 2 automation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a35785277/tesla-fsd-california-self-driving/ |first=Roberto |last=Baldwin |date=March 9, 2021 |title=Tesla Tells California DMV that FSD Is Not Capable of Autonomous Driving |website=[[Car and Driver]] }}</ref> In a May 2021 study by Guidehouse Insights, Tesla was ranked last for both strategy and execution in the autonomous driving sector.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Abuelsamid|first1=Sam|last2=Shepard|first2=Scott|date=May 20, 2021|title=Guidehouse Insights Names Waymo, Nvidia, Argo AI, and Baidu the Leading Companies Developing Automated Driving Systems (Executive Summary)|url=https://guidehouseinsights.com/-/media/project/navigant-research/navigant-research-executive-summaries/2021/2q-2021/guidehouse-insights-leaderboard-automated-driving-systems-executive-summarypdf.pdf|access-date=May 24, 2021|website=Guidehouse Insights}}{{link note|note=Registration required}}</ref> In October 2021, the [[National Transportation Safety Board]] (NTSB) called on Tesla to change the design of its Autopilot to ensure it cannot be misused by drivers, according to a letter sent to Musk.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 26, 2021 |first=Kirsten |last=Korosec |title=NTSB chair calls on Elon Musk to change design of Tesla Autopilot |url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/10/25/ntsb-chair-elon-musk-change-tesla-autopilot/ |work=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref>

=== Assembly technology ===
Tesla has pioneered the use of massive casting machines ([[Giga Press]]), to make large single pieces of vehicle underbodies and to streamline production.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://europe.autonews.com/suppliers/giga-presses-help-toyota-volvo-hyundai-cut-production-costs |title=Giga Presses -- the giant die casts that are reshaping car manufacturing |agency=Reuters |location=US |via=Automotive News |date=February 10, 2023 |access-date=March 1, 2023}}</ref>

In September 2022, Tesla revealed prototypes of its proposed humanoid robot [[Optimus (robot)|Optimus]], which Musk has stated uses the same core software as FSD. During the presentations at Tesla's AI Day 2022, Musk suggested that, among other use cases, the finalized version of Optimus could be used in Tesla's car factories to help with repetitive tasks and relieve labor shortages.<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Meghan |last1=Bobrowsky |first2=Rebecca |last2=Elliott |date=September 30, 2022 |title=Elon Musk Unveils Prototype of Tesla's Humanoid Robot Optimus, Says It Will Cost Less Than a Car |work=The Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-ai-day-2022-elon-musk-11664536415 |access-date=October 2, 2022 |issn=0099-9660}}</ref>

=== Glass ===
In November 2016, the company announced the Tesla glass technology group. The group produced the roof glass for the Tesla Model 3. It also produces the glass used in the [[Tesla Solar Roof]]'s [[solar shingle]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Muoio |first=Danielle |title=Elon Musk: Tesla is developing a special kind of glass for its Model 3 |website=[[Business Insider]] |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-tesla-model-3-will-use-glass-from-solar-roof-2016-11 |date=November 1, 2016}}</ref>

== Facilities ==
{{See also|List of Tesla factories}}

